<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Raps SADC Political Parties on Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has taken a swipe at some political parties in the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) region who only
respect the results of elections if they are winners.
</P>
<P>
At a banquet hosted by Malawian President Bakili Muluzi last
night in Malawi's commercial city Blantyre, Chiluba told the
heads of state and government who gathered for the 17th SADC
summit that such party leaders think there is no democracy until
they come into power, the official Zambia News Agency ZANA
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president did not name those political parties or
their leaders.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, a former trade union leader who succeeded Zambia's
veteran statesman Kenneth Kaunda as president in the 1991
multia-party elections and was re-elected in 1996, cautioned his
counterparts that the danger of some people in Africa is that
they have tourist impressions about democracy.
</P>
<P>
"They go for a few weeks abroad. They come back as experts and
they want to tell you: you are actually not democratic enough,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
He said that an interesting aspect about such leaders is that
they compare their countries to Britain and yet they do not know
when the Briton's uncodified constitution began or when the U.S.
got its independence from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Africa is going through a democratic process, which can be
evidenced by the recorded growth rate in the SADC members'
economies, concluded the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
