<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Conducts Study on Tourism Among Member Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's
executive agency today called on small and medium-sized tourism
operators in EU member countries to improve awareness of "yield
management" in their business.
</P>
<P>
They were adviced to pay more attention to business statistics,
training, improved flow of information on the best methods and
practices, the need to build partnerships and enhancing
cooperation in marketing.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations were made after the European Commission
conducted a close study on yield management and profit
maximization in small and medium-sized enterprises in the tourism
sector.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the levels of awareness of yield
management vary greatly among the 17-member countries of the
European Economic Area.
</P>
<P>
Countries with limited knowledge of yield management are
Greece, Iceland, Luxembourg and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Finland, Britain, Austria, Ireland, Italy and Spain
are countries with moderate knowledge, while Denmark, France,
Germany, the Netherlands, Norway and Sweden are found to possess
broad awareness of yield management practices.
</P>
<P>
As a way of strengthening competitiveness in Europe's tourism
industry, yield management as a systematic approach to profit
maximization has emerged in the last few years among larger
tourism-oriented enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Chritos Papoutsis, European commissioner in charge of tourism,
said the study showed yield management can contribute to the
competitiveness of European tourism by strengthening and
supporting the performance of its enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism, being one of the biggest industries, contributes
significantly to employment," he said. "We must encourage tourism
enterprises to use profit maximization practices in their business.
</P>
<P>
"Yield management should be encouraged and supported through
action in the areas that have been identified," he added.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that despite the fact that Europe's
tourism industry continues to grow in terms of volume and
receipts, it is facing increasing competition from other
continents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
