<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government to Challenge Fishing Quota Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
considering to challenge a British High Court ruling that Spanish
fishermen are entitled to claim millions of pounds of compensation
because of being barred from using British fishing quotas.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Fisheries Minister Ellliot Morley was quoted by the
Financial Times as saying Monday that the government would argue
in court that the previous administration had followed proper
advice and acted reasonably in excluding quota-hoppers.
</P>
<P>
Quota-hoppers are referred to those Spanish and Dutch-owned
vessels that register in Britain to gain access to British
national fishing quotas.
</P>
<P>
Britain is also planning to seek permission from Spain later
next week for spot checks on Spanish ships fishing British waters
but landing the catch in Spanish ports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The British government will also present proposals to the
European Commission within the next few weeks on measures to force
quota-hoppers to share the economic benefits of their catches with
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, London promised to launch a further crackdown on
illegal fishing by British fishing vessels by outlawing purchases
of "black fish," fish caught in excess of quotas, by processors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
