<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Urged to Invest in Zambia's Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's water supply sector
has appealed to local and foreign investors to invest in the
sector which needs about 800 million U.S. Dollars for water
supply improvement.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Mwanza, head of the water sector development group
which has been put in place to spearhead the commercialization of
the sector, made this appeal in Lusaka Monday, an
English-language newspaper Zambia Daily Mail said today.
</P>
<P>
Private involvement is vital if the sector has to improve its
services, Mwanza stated, while disclosing that the Zambian
government would create regulators to ensure that there is
efficiency after the water sector is commercialized.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Mwanza as saying that the water sector has
not been able to meet its obligations due to poor funding and
lack of skilled human resources.
</P>
<P>
He said government investment in the sector has been declining,
making it difficult for the people responsible to maintain and
replace infrastructure which has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza added that poor financial resources have also made it
impossible for the sector to meet the costs of extending water
services to all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is rich in water resources. It has 40 percent of the
water resources of southern Africa which, if properly utilized,
would contribute effectively to its national development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
