<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September -- France Tuesday called on factions of the
Congo Republic to continue peace talks on national reconciliation
in Libreville and refrain from sinking deeper into the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The search for a consensual solution (by Congolese factions)
remains essential," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt. (France-Congo Republic-Appeal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Some 75 delegates from 15 countries and regions will
gather in Manila to attend the 20th Annual Meeting of the
Federation of ASEAN Shippers' Council (FASC) on October 1-3.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Reyes, director of the Philippine Shippers' Bureau of
the Department of Trade and Industry, said the conference will
discuss the recent world trade development, industry concerns and
various matters affecting the FASC members and international
community. (Philippines-ASEAN-Shippers Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said
Tuesday Russia would never allow separatism to exist and it will
certainly protect its territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
After attending the reopening ceremony of the State Museum of
Russian History, Chernomyrdin told reporters that Russia has been
and will always be an integral state and any attempt threatening
its territorial integrity would fail. (Russia-Integrity)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Austin Hu, acting head of the World Bank's China
mission, told Xinhua Tuesday that "the World Bank has built up a
mature and close co-operative partnership with China and such
partnership will continue for a long time."
</P>
<P>
China is an important partner of the World Bank and it is ready
to develop its close co-operation with China further, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank approved financial aid for 184 projects in China by
the end of June, involving nearly 27.97 billion U.S. dollars.
(China-World Bank)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- European Commission President Jacques Santer has once
again called for a punctual start of the planned single European
currency, the euro, saying that a delay in its 1999 launch was
"unimaginable," German media reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Deutschlandradio Berlin on Tuesday,
Santer voiced sharp criticism over recent debates in Germany about
a possible delay of the euro. (EU-Euro) 
</P>
