<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela on Mobutu's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Former Zairean President
Mobutu Sese Seko was "snubbed" in his last days by countries
which had benefited from a long association with him, South
African President Nelson Mandela said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at his residence, Mandela
criticized Mobutu's former western allies without naming them.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Mobutu's friends deserted him when he was in need
of humanitarian assistance and described how he tried to persuade
these countries to offer medical treatment to this ailing man.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu died of prostate cancer in Morocco Sunday. His three
decades of power in Zaire ended in May this year when he was
ousted by rebel leader Laurent Kabila, who renamed the country
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"As you know, I met Mobutu in his capital and at the United
Nations. I had the opportunity of interacting with him. After he
stepped down, I tried to get him medical treatment in Morocco and
other places," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
"But his former friends for 30 years and who benefited from
their association with him, on his last days on earth, they did
not want to know him," claimed the South African leader.
</P>
<P>
"No matter what he did in the past, he required humanitarian
treatment. Whatever his politics, his passing away was a
tragedy," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
