<HEADLINE> Demirel's Egypt Trip to Allay Arab Fear: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish ambassador to Egypt
said today that Turkish President Suleyman Demirel's planned
one-day visit to Egypt next Tuesday will help allay Arabs' concern
over growing Israeli-Turkish cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Yacar Yakic said Arab-Turkish ties, Mideast affairs
and several other issues of mutual interest would figure high on
the agenda of Demirel's talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, according to the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Demirel's visit falls within the context of continued
consultations between the Egyptian and Turkish leaderships, the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
"The trip would help lessen the Arabs' fears over Turkey's
possible estrangement from the Arab world and its rapprochement
with Israel," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has always used its open channels with Israel to serve
the Palestinian cause, he said, citing an example how Ankara
voiced its condemnation of the Israeli settlement policy during
the recent visit paid by Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Yakis said that Demirel's visit is aimed at
"dispelling fears of Turkey's likely distancing itself from the
Arab world and getting closer to Israel."
</P>
<P>
He dismissed that the relations between Ankara and Tel Aviv are
"of any dimensions causing anxiety."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed a military cooperation accord in
February 1996. They have announced that they would stage joint
naval exercises together with the United States in the eastern
Mediterranean on November 15-25.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers provoked outcries from Arab countries,
especially Syria, which sees itself as the target of the
Turkish-Israeli alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Turkish summit, which was originally set for May,
was postponed in the wake of the planned naval war games.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said that Turkey and
Israel sent a "negative message" to the region by planning the
exercises.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said earlier that the Egyptian-Turkish
talks would focus on means to enhance relations between the two
countries and increase the volume of trade exchange to one billion
dollars annually, the situation in northern Iraq, as well as the
Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
