<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Move Toward Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia today advanced toward the main opposition stronghold of
Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Kabul, reports monitored
here said.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross and United Nations suspended flights to the city,
stronghold of anti-Taliban strongman Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik,
and aid workers there were told to stay in shelters, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban claimed today in a radio broadcast to have captured
the Mazar-e-Sharif airport, which is eight kilometers east of the
city, but Malik's forces said they still had control of the
airport.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban advance, which cut off the two main roads into
Mazar-e-Sharif, came as fighting erupted inside the city itself
between soldiers loyal to Malik and those loyal to their former
boss Rashid Dostum who was deposed by Malik in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
