<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Environment Workshop Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A three-day workshop on
Zimbabwe's environment started here today to assess its
requirements and projects.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the workshop, Mines, Environment and
Tourism Deputy Minister Chindori Chininga said, ''environmental
assessment is a basic tool for project planning and
implementation to ensure environmental and socio-economic costs
and benefits of the projects and avoid unwarranted negative
impacts.''
</P>
<P>
He said the primary objective of the workshop is to explore
opportunities to harmonize the zimbabwean environmental impact
assessment procedures and requirements.
</P>
<P>
Of major concern to Zimbabwe was the need to identify ways and
means to enhance environmental assessment preparation within the
processing of projects proposed for financing by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chininga said for many years now Zimbabwe had placed emphasis
on the economic costs and benefits of developmental projects with
little regard being put on environmental impacts. The government
and most organizations had come to appreciate environmental
costs.
</P>
<P>
He added his ministry is working on incorporating
environmental impact assessment into a legislative proposal being
drafted.
</P>
<P>
The government, said Chininga, will soon start environmental
impact assessment training which is to be conducted across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's environmental impact assessment policy, which
intergrates environmental assessment into every phase of the
project cycle, was designed in 1994 to encourage development
proponents to identify and minimize negative environmental
benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
