<HEADLINE> S. Africans Asked Not to Be Losers in Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
today urged his fellow South Africans to show sportsmanship and
accept the failure of Cape Town's bid to host the 2004 Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
Those who thought South Africa would sail to victory in its
Olympic Games bid were people who lived in a fool's paradise,
Mandela told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
"I have congratulated (winning city) Athens. Greece is a great
country," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee on September 5 named
Athens the winner of the 2004 Olympics bid, beating Cape Town,
Stockholm, Buenos Aires and Rome.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said: "it is regrettable of course that Africa could
not host the games for the first time, but we must reflect the
spirit of sportsmanship."
</P>
<P>
Cape Town was biding on behalf of the African continent under
the support of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said there was fair play in the choice of Athens
because the International Olympic Committee was composed of
fair-minded people.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has said a few days ago that his country will discuss
the possibility of South Africa's continuation of biding for 2008
Olympic Games. 
</P>
