<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Asked to Participate in Anti-Drug Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China issued a notice today
asking local governments to encourage women to join the anti-drug
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The notice, issued by the National Narcotics Control Commission
and the All-China Women's Federation, asked women's federations at
all levels to publicize the state's policies, laws and regulations
against drugs, and the threat that drugs posed to the country
in the modern history.
</P>
<P>
Women should be aware of the serious physical and psychological
damages caused by drugs, the notice said, adding that they should
improve their anti-drug knowledge and have a better understanding
of the state's anti-drug policies, laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Stress should be put on families with addicts, the notice
said.
</P>
<P>
It also asked women's federations to organize activities such
as lectures and consultative services to make the anti-drug
program known in every family.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the notice asked women to inform authorities about
illegal drug-related activities.
</P>
<P>
Women's federations should set up educational networks to
prevent the emergence of new addicts and drug-traffickers, the
notice said, asking the federations to care for and help women
addicts, especially the young, to break from their past.
</P>
<P>
The notice said that the women's federations should build a
line of defense among women and their families in the battle
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
People should be appointed to take charge of the work in
federations at all levels, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should also be made to guarantee drug-free families, it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
