<HEADLINE> Russia, Chechnya Sign Agreements on Oil Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia and its republic of
Chechnya today signed several agreements on how to use an oil
pipeline, which runs through the republic, to transport oil to
Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the agreements were
signed after two days of negotiations between the representatives
of Russia's Fuel and Power Ministry and the Chechen South Oil
Company.
</P>
<P>
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov was present
at the signing ceremony. He later told reporters that the
agreements cover security arrangements for oil pipeline workers,
pipeline remaking and protection, oil shipment and fees.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Azerbaijan and Chechnya signed an agreement on July 11,
enabling Azerbaijan to use the pipeline that runs through Chechnya
to the Russian city of Novorossiysk on the coast of Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The 1,400-kilometer-long pipeline starts from Baku and ends at
Novorossiysk and of it a section of 150 kilometers is in
Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
