<HEADLINE> SADC Commends Zambia for Democratization: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba
said here today that the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) has commended Zambia for its democratization process,
according to the official Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
On his return to the Lusaka international airport from
Malawi's southern city Blantyre, where he attended the 17th SADC
summit, Chiluba told journalists that the commendation made in
writing praised Zambia for putting in place institutional
arrangements necessary in any democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia has been commended for the democratization process. We
are one of the those countries with democratic institutional
arrangements and I am extremely happy," said the Zambian
president.
</P>
<P>
However, Chiluba did not give further details.
</P>
<P>
Last night, at a banquet given by Malawian President Bakili
Muluzi in Blantyre for the heads of state and government
attending the SADC summit, Chiluba took a swipe at some political
parties in the region who only respect the results of elections
if they are winners.
</P>
<P>
He criticized such unnamed parties for their liking to compare
the democracy in their countries with that in some western
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the airport, Chiluba warned that Zambians should
not be complacent, saying the achievements scored so far should
be used as a basis for further progress.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that there is need to keep the rule of law in
his country, claiming Zambia's democratic record is "so good"
that some non-governmental organizations and "selfish"
individuals are taking advantages and are going round playing
tricks.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba did not say who those bodies and individuals are.
</P>
<P>
While in a recent development in Zambia, it is believed that
police fired live ammunition to disperse an Opposition rally,
during which former President Kenneth Kaunda, now President of
the United National Independence Party (UNIP) and another
opposition leader were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Zambia began its democratic process in the early 1990s with
the introduction of a multi-party system. It is democratization
that has brought Chiluba, a former trade union leader, came into
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
