<HEADLINE> Bonn Tightens Eastern Border Control Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- German Interior Minister Manfred
Kanther today ordered an increase in the police force guarding the
borders with the Czech Republic and Poland in a bid to block
illegal immigrants into Germany.
</P>
<P>
Kanther said he was ordering a further 1,500 border troops to
be permanently stationed on the eastern borders, adding to 5,800
officers of the Bundesgrenzschutz -- Germany's Federal Border
Guard -- currently deployed there.
</P>
<P>
The move was also partly directed at the rising crime rate in
that region, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kanther said 15,397 illegal immigrants were stopped while
trying to sneak into Germany in the first half of this year, up
from 11,779 in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of illegal foreigners caught after
entering Germany rose to 3,622, compared with 3,089 a year before.
</P>
<P>
"Germany's eastern borders remain the focal point for illegal
immigration and smuggling of foreigners," said Kanther. He noted
that the German-Czech border was becoming more important as a
transit route.
</P>
<P>
The largest group trying to enter Germany illegally is from
Romania, which was followed by Iraq, Bulgaria and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesgrenzschutz has been strengthening its force on the
eastern borders over recent years in efforts to reduce the number
of illegal immigrants. It has a total of some 34,000 officers,
which controls the country's borders and also plays a big role in
combating organized crime and drug smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Poor People Have Shorter Life Expectancy: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Life expectancy for people at
the bottom end of the social and economic ladder in Britain tends
to be shorter than those at the top, according to an official
study published today.
</P>
<P>
The study, titled Health Inequality, by the Office for National
Statistics (ONS) found that men at the bottom end of the social
scale had trebled the rate of mortality in 1991-93 compared with
those at the top. The rate for women during the same time was one
and a half times.
</P>
<P>
Mortality rates for poor men from lung cancer during the period
were five times greater than for those at the top end of the
social scale. For women, the rates were three times higher at the
bottom than at the top.
</P>
<P>
Men at the bottom of the social ladder tended to live five
years shorter than those at the top while for women at the bottom,
life expectancy was three years less than for those at the top.
</P>
<P>
The government welcomed the report's exposure of what it called
"two Britains divided by ever-widening health inequality."
</P>
<P>
However, it said such entrenched inequality would not be
reversed overnight. "To make a real difference, we need long term
policies," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Financial Times Launches US Edition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's leading business
newspaper The Financial Times (FT) launched today a U.S. edition
in an effort to boost its international circulation.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was part of the newspaper's pledge of injecting
some 100 million pounds (about 160 million U.S. dollars) over the
next five years to lift its international sales to 430,000 from
300,000.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. edition, to be published in New Jersey and California,
is aimed at boosting U.S. circulation from some 37,000 to around
100,000 over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
FT editor Richard Lambert was quoted as saying in today's
London FT edition, "In the U.S., we will not be seeking to
replicate existing newspapers."
</P>
<P>
"Instead we plan to offer a broader view of the world than is
currently available," Lambert said. "Our aim is to win the battle
for a little time on the daily schedule of busy and influential
people."
</P>
<P>
The FT has published two versions, its main British edition and
an international edition, with around 140,000 of its 300,000 daily
sales, printed at its eight overseas sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
