<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus-Greece War Games to Go Ahead: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has lifted the air ban
on Greek warplanes to facilitate an annual joint military
exercises with Greece scheduled for later this year, Defense
Minister Costas Eliades said here today.
</P>
<P>
The decision to suspend Greek warplanes' flights over Cyprus
was taken last April to create a positive climate for the
U.N.-sponsored direct peace talks between Greek and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' National Guard military exercises with the Greek air
force, code-named "Nikiforos 97," will take place later this year
as planned, the minister told the press, but stopping short of
giving further details.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have a close military link with a joint
defense pact signed in 1993, under which Greece pledges to join
Cyprus in resisting any possible military attack.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, which was
declared by the Turkish Cypriot in 1983 as "The Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus", recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The two rounds of direct peace talks between Cypriot President
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in July and
August have ended in a failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
