<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Rampant in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaria is taking the death
toll of many Somalis in many regions of southern Somalia due to
the rainy season which still continues.
</P>
<P>
According to the health authorities of Merca town, 100 KM
south of the capital, more than 30 patients suffering from severe
malaria reach the outdoor patient clinic of the COSV, or Italian
aid agency-run hospital of the town every day.
</P>
<P>
Dr Omar Osman Ahmed, a pediatrician at the hospital said six
people, mainly children, have died of the disease since the past
week in the region. "The last was a nine-year-old girl who died
in the hospital three days ago."
</P>
<P>
There are nine mother and child health care posts throughout
the nine districts of the region. Dr Ahmed said these posts offer
free chloroquine tablets to mild cases of the malaria victims
while quinine is treated with those severe and complicated cases.
</P>
<P>
"We can't provide mosquito nets, but we give them public
awareness lessons," said Dr Ahmed, "We tell them to burn the
residue of the maize in their huts to make smoke which rebels the
anopheles."
</P>
<P>
Severe cases of malaria is also being reported from the Lower
Jubba and Middle Shabelle regions where more than seven death
cases were registered by the local treatment centers since last
month.
</P>
<P>
In Jowhar town, the capital of Middle Shabelle region, 40 to
50 people suffering from cerebral malaria reach the hospital of
the town every day, according to Mr Mohamed Mohamud Bishar, the
director of the main hospital there.
</P>
<P>
The malaria cases are not confined to the regions alone, but
the capital city of the country is also being affected by the
disease. Dr Osman Mohamud Dufle, the coordinator of the Joint
Health Authority of Mogadishu, confirmed to journalists that
there are sporadic deaths of malaria victims.
</P>
<P>
"The current major killer diseases are malaria and
tuberculosis," said Dr Dufle, the only internist of the war torn
capital.
</P>
<P>
One of the largest private hospitals in South Mogadishu had
received 65 malaria cases since the beginning of the month with
three deaths. Among the patients were 15 wounded militiamen who
were hit by malaria while receiving dressing treatments.
</P>
<P>
Dr Abdi Mohamed Hangul, the director of Dr Hassan Jiis
Memorial hospital, said the malaria germ seems to be gaining
resistance to the chloroquine tablets.
</P>
<P>
The people of Somalia are not only missing adequate medical
care, but also lack laboratories and x-rays for diagnosing
varieties of deadly diseases including malaria and tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The few available facilities of this kind are very expensive
so that the common people cannot afford, as there is no single
aid agency that provides such help, observers here say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Takes Difficult Trip Into Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Madeleine Albright started
her first trip to the Middle East as secretary of state today with
a very difficult mission to revive the already tattered peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. officials said they saw little chance for Albright to
make an improvement in terms of relations between Israel and the
Palestinians with such an entrenched crisis of confidence.
</P>
<P>
"When you begin to see the kind of erosion (in the peace
process) that we have, you have to re-establish the basics to be
able to move forward," a senior State Department official told
reporters on the eve of Albright's departure this morning.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Lewis, former U.S. ambassador to Israel, even said
Albright's long-delayed visit to the region "has made the trip
more vulnerable to failure."
</P>
<P>
Yahya Sadowski of Brookings Institution, a Middle East analyst,
agreed to Lewis' remarks. He said that the whole peace process is
rapidly unraveling and Albright is going out with no new ideas for
the resolving of the crisis of confidence.
</P>
<P>
"She only has the rather desperate hope that a renewed
expression of American interest will keep hope alive," Sadowski
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in the Middle East, Albright will ask
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to step up crackdown of
militants, rupture the terrorism infrastructure and make good on
the promise to safeguard Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
She will also tell Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu:
Israel should not use safety as a pretext to side track
indefinitely the commitments his labor predecessors had made to
the Palestinian Authority for phased withdrawal on the West Bank.
And she will also try to persuade the Israeli prime minister to
suspend the extension of Jewish settlements in Arab residential
areas.
</P>
<P>
But the stances of Israel and the Palestinians are so polarized
that Albright could hardly make any advance in bridging their
differences through just one visit.
</P>
<P>
The White House said Monday that Albright will not make any
pressures on both sides. "Is is not wise for someone attempting to
facilitate a dialogue to play the role of a heavy hand," it said.
</P>
<P>
Albright's travel to some other Arab nations shows that apart
from trying to revive the moribund peace process, the United
States is exerting its effort to maintain a loose coalition
between Arab states and Israel, built after the Persian Gulf war
to contain Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But, with the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians
in tatters and the chance of a comprehensive Middle East peace
fading, the prospect of that coalition is also fraying.
</P>
<P>
The possible abortion of an American-sponsored Middle East
economic summit meeting, scheduled to be held in mid-November in
Doha, Qatar, signals that fraying, as Saudi Arabia and some other
Gulf states have made it clear they might not attend the meeting,
in which Israel would take part.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said success on her trip has not been precooked,
and it will be hard even to define. And Albright's aides have
already said: "She is not a magician." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
