<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Agrees to Mitchell Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political party
of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), formally agreed today to the
so-called Mitchell Principles of democracy and non-violence.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Belfast, the capital of Northern Ireland, quoted
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams as saying, "It is a defining
moment."
</P>
<P>
Adams, whose party has been excluded from the all-party peace
talks on Northern Ireland, said, "Sinn Fein's attitude... is to
get all of the guns out of Irish politics."
</P>
<P>
The pledge came as Sinn Fein attended the first session of the
Stormont talks which have made slow progress since their launch in
June 1996.
</P>
<P>
But Protestant Unionist parties boycotted today's preliminary
session, expressing scepticism over Sinn Fein's commitment to
peace.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the boycott, political analysts here said that it
was an ominous portent for the opening of the talks due to taking
place next week.
</P>
<P>
Unionist politicians, speaking for the majority Protestants who
are determined to remain under British rule, regard the IRA
cease-fire as bogus and are angry that Sinn Fein has been given a
seat while its guerrilla wing retains vast arsenals.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair said that the government would hold
Sinn Fein to its commitment to the Mitchell Principles with "total
determination."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Blair would meet Unionist leader David
Trimble in London Wednesday to urge him to join the all-party
talks.
</P>
<P>
The government has also promised to set up an international
body to oversee the issue by the time negotiations start next
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
