<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana's Chauffeur Definitely Drunk: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Henri Paul, the 41-year-old
security chief of the Hotel Ritz who crashed the Mercedes S-280
carrying Princess Diana, was definitely drunk when the accident
took place.
</P>
<P>
A third examination of the bloodstream of Paul showed that the
rate of alcohol containment in his blood was 1.8 grams per liter,
more than three times higher than the 0.5 gram per liter legal
limit, said Agence France-Presse quoting reliable sources.
</P>
<P>
The previous two examinations of Paul's bloodstream showed that
the alcohol containment rate in his blood was 1.75 grams per liter
and 1.82 grams per liter.
</P>
<P>
This over-high rate means that a man of 65 to 75 kilograms
heavy has drunk eight to nine cups of alcohol drink containing 81
to 94 grams of pure alcohol.
</P>
<P>
The third examination was ordered by an investigation judge at
the demand of the family of Paul.
</P>
<P>
All three examinations were conducted by different experts from
different institutions appointed by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The previous two examinations were conducted above the level of
his heart, while the last one was made on the level of his legs.
</P>
<P>
Paul's employer, the Hotel Ritz of Paris which is owned by the
family of Dodi al Fayed, who was also killed in the August 30
mid-night crash, had presented security video tapes showing Paul
talking and walking "normally" that night.
</P>
<P>
French police investigators are now inclined to the hypothesis
that the fatal crash which killed Princess Diana was directly
caused by over-speeding of her car and drunkenness of the
chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
If this hypothesis is established finally, the 10 photographers
under inquiry will not be found guilty for having pursued Diana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
