<HEADLINE> Gas Turbine Generator In Dar es Salaam Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- One of the
power-generating gas turbines in the Tanzanian capital has broken
down, which adds more difficulty to power supply in the city.
</P>
<P>
After Tanzania experienced power rationing four years ago it
imported from the United States gas turbines and installed them
at Ubungo in Dar es Salaam, which injected about 40 megawatts to
the national power grid.
</P>
<P>
The Acting Managing Director of Tanzania Electric Supply
Company (TANESC), Kiyaro Iranga, told the local press today that
this was the second time that the generator had developed a
mishap but he said an expert had been dispatched from the
suppliers to come to repair it.
</P>
<P>
Iranga also said that there was not enough stocks in the fuel
tanks at the Ubungo power station and TANESCO had no funds to
afford fuel to run the four gas turbines there for 24 hours in
the light of dropping water levels at two dams which support the
country's major generators.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing started on Monday in Dar es Salaam and other
regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
"Even if our customers paid their bills, it would still be
difficult for TANESCO to run the generators and break even. The
weather-lack of rain since 1992 to 1996 and this year has
contributed a lot to the company's problem," Irango said, adding,
"We need about three years of good rain in order to stabilize the
power problem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
