<HEADLINE> Date of Somali Reconciliation Conference Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Somali former foreign minister
Mohamed Ali Hamed said today Somali faction leaders will hold a
national reconciliation congress in Bosaso, south of the Somali
capital of Mogadishu, on November 1.
</P>
<P>
Hamed informed Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid
of the decision during a meeting here today, which he said tackled
ways to render the expected congress a success, according to the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Somali factions have agreed to put an end to the
fierce crisis in the country which has been going on for seven
years in order to restore stability and security, Hamed said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by leader of the Somali Salvation
Alliance Ali Mahdi Mohamed and leader of the Somali Congress Party
Hussein Farah Aideed, together with a number of Somali National
Salvation Council leaders.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders signed a reconciliation agreement in the
Egyptian capital of Cairo on May 29 on holding peace talks to end
the civil war that has ravaged the country since 1991. Egypt has
been involved in mediating an end to the six-year-old Somali
crisis in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
As for the Cairo agreement, Hamed said such an important treaty
is still in force and all the factions endeavor to implement it.
</P>
<P>
The projected meeting is to discuss means of pushing forward
efforts that are aimed at holding an overall and expanded national
reconciliation conference including all Somali conflicting
factions.
</P>
<P>
Hamed and other members of the Somali National Salvation
Council are making a tour of a number of Arab countries to gain
support for their plan that is aimed at achieving Somali
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League is currently coordinating efforts with the U.N.
and the Organization of African Unity as well as major countries
in the area such as Egypt and Ethiopia to activate the Somali
reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 ouster of the late president Mohamed Siad Barre,
Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by faction
leaders, who continued to fight to expand their turfs despite
several unsuccessful peace conferences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
