<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Sum Up Peace Keeping in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A full set of documentation
will be produced to review how west African countries worked to
restore peace to Liberia after a seven-year bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is to
launch the special documentation project along with a
commemorative stamp during next year's ECOWAS summit, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project and stamps will be launched in Abuja, capital of
Nigeria, to generate funds for the cash-strapped 16-member
organization.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the project is necessitated by the
need to produce an authentic documentation on the justification
for the intervention and foster the application of the lessons of
the initiative in advancing ECOWAS' objectives.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to maintain stability in the sub-region, ECOWAS
leaders in 1990 sent a peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to
Liberia to help end the factional fightings ignited by the battle
launched by the current President Charles Taylor in 1989 against
the previous administration.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has successfully disarmed and demobilized the warring
factions, paving the way for the country's election in July which
led Taylor to the top seat he had fought for.
</P>
<P>
The planned documentation project, according to the report,
will also determine how the sub-regional body's success could be
developed as a model of west African response to regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will highlight the special role played by
ECOWAS in anchoring the peace process, will involve a review of
the agreements preceeding the last one signed in Abuja last
August, as well as interviews with key players in the process
within and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
It will also involve the review of academic publications,
video documentation and other materials, in addition to
organizing seminars to collect expert opinions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the issuance of the commemorative stamps throughout
the sub-region is aimed to foster African brotherfood, highlight
the role of ECOMOG for prosperity and cement the solidarity of
west African troops, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
