<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Chief: Talks With Iraq Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The chief U.N. weapons
inspector today described his negotiations with the Iraqi
authorities on dismantling Iraq's mass-destruction weapons as
open, candid and very fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, head of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of dismantling Iraqi mass-destruction weapons, said at a
news conference here before leaving for New York that he
and the Iraqi side focussed in their discussions on the program
agreed upon last July, particularly in the missile and chemical
fields.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that further talks in these two fields would take
place in the future.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here last Friday, leading a seven-man team of
arms experts. This is his second visit to Iraq after his
appointment as head of the UNSCOM on July 1.
</P>
<P>
During his first visit to Iraq, Butler reached an agreement
with the Iraqi authorities on the working plan for the removal of
the Iraqi ballistic, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
At the news conference, Butler said that Iraq had communicated
to the UNSCOM a full and comprehensive statement on biological
weapons, and would provide further clarifications and information
about them within the next two days.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the results of laboratory analysis of the
Scud missiles destroyed by Iraq were identical and consistent with
the related Iraqi announcements.
</P>
<P>
Butler pointed out that he is preparing a report to the
U.N. Security Council on the status of Iraq's weapons program.
</P>
</TEXT>
