<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Wall Street's Volatility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
ended down today, depressed by domestic concerns, Wall Street's
unsteady start and a weak dollar.
</P>
<P>
In London, the FTSE 100 index ended down 0.7 percent or 34.7
points at 4,950.5, hit by profit-taking and weak futures, but
above the day's low on the back of an about-turn on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that activity was subdued ahead of the Bank of
England monetary meeting Wednesday, though rates are not expected
to rise.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended 0.65 percent higher on the
DAX-30 index, supported by a strong car sector which was boosted
by news from the Frankfurt car show.
</P>
<P>
The index rose by 26.38 points to 4,094.39 by the close.
Dealers said inflation and jobless data painted a less than
positive picture of the economy.
</P>
<P>
However, in later screen-based trade, the IBIS index ended down
26.69 points at 4,104.57.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, shares finished weaker in quiet trading as
investors adjusted their positions following Monday's 0.6 percent
rise. The CAC-40 index closed 21.17 points down at 2,919.72.
