<HEADLINE> Cuba Supports Iraq's Efforts to Lift Sanctions: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Deputy Minister of
Foreign Affairs Aiomilio Cabajero today expressed Cuba's support
for the Iraqi efforts to lift the U.N. sanctions imposed since
1990 for its invasion of Kuwait, Iraqi news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Cabajero made the statement here at the meeting with Iraqi
Finance Minister Hikmat Azawi, during which they also exchanged
views on the prospects of promoting economic cooperation between
Cuba and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban deputy foreign minister denounced the U.S. policies
to obstruct the implementation of the oil-for-food accord, which
was signed between U.N. and Iraq in May last year and went into
effect last December.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars
of oil within six months to buy food and badly needed medicine,
was renewed last June.
</P>
<P>
Cabajero has also had a meeting with Senior Undersecretary of
the Iraqi Ministry of Health Shawki Morcos on promoting
cooperation in the field of health, as well as Cuba's
participation in providing Iraq with medical drugs and supplies
under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Cabajero arrived in Baghdad Sunday evening on a two-day visit
to Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
