<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Economy in Slowing-down Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus' economy is
apparently locked in a slowing-down trend as the growth rate for
1998 was budgeted at 2 percent today.
</P>
<P>
The economy's growing pace, which was at around 5 percent in
1995, slowed down to 3 percent last year and is expected to keep
a 3.5 percent this year. A flagging tourism has been put on blame.
</P>
<P>
But emerging from the cabinet meeting which approved the 1998
budget, Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said the 2
percent growth rate would appear favorable when compared with
those of the European Union (EU) member states.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for a full membership of the EU in 1990 and has
adjusted its statistics system to make figures comparable with
those of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The budget envisages an expenditure of 1,629.9 million Cyprus
pounds (3,064.2 million U.S. dollars) and a deficit of 550 million
pounds (1,034 million dollars). The deficit represents a 41.5
percent increase over that expected for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said in a statement that large
infrastructure projects concerning water and road enjoy priorities
in the development sector of the budget.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said the budget is aimed at achieving
government's goal of "economic stability, expansion of production
capacity and a fairer distribution of the national revenue."
</P>
</TEXT>
