<HEADLINE> Turkey Seized 2 Tonnes of Drugs in 8 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Around two tonnes of narcotics
has been seized in Turkey so far this year, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,300 people, including 183 foreigners, were
arrested in the 1,180 anti-drugs operations launched by the police
throughout the country during the period, Security Department
officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This represents a significant drop in the volume of the drugs
seized by the police because of a change in the smuggling routes
in Turkey, they said.
</P>
<P>
The "Balkan route" has been replaced by the "norther Black Sea
route," they added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been known as an important route for
trafficking drugs into the European markets from Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish police seized 4.4 tonnes of heroin in 1996,
accounting for 40 percent of the world's total haul, and 12 tonnes
of hashish, official figures show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
