<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Big Five" to Re-draw Future Economic Map: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The next 25 years will
witness an unprecedented boost in the prominence of developing
countries in the world economy, and five of those nations are
likely to change the world economic map, the World Bank predicted.
</P>
<P>
In its 114-page report "Global Economic Prospects and the
Developing Countries 1997" released here today, the World Bank
said policy reforms and a broadly favorable international economic
environment could allow developing countries to grow between 5 to
6 percent between now and 2020, raising their share of world
output from around one-sixth to nearly one third over the period.
</P>
<P>
The growing importance of developing economies will be
reflected in, and driven by, the emergence of the "Big Five" --
China, India, Brazil, Indonesia and Russia -- which now account
for half of the world's labor force but only 8 to 10 percent of
its output and trade. Given continued policy reforms and the
strengthening of an open world trade and investment regime, the
report projected, these figures could double by 2020, with
substantial repercussions for global resource allocation,
production, trade and also pricing.
</P>
<P>
Trade relationships will be transformed, the report said. The
current Big Five nations' share of world trade is only a third of
that of the European Union, but by 2020, it could surge to 50
percent higher than that of the EU. The rapid growth of developing
countries will have far-reaching effects, with substantial
benefits for most regions and countries in the world. Developing
countries will provide an ever more important market for
industrial country exports, the share going to developing
countries being expected to rise from 25 to 40 percent between
1992 and 2020.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report noted that the international economic
environment for developing countries remains favorable, which is
characterized by broadly stable world macroeconomic conditions,
expanding flows of private capital to developing countries, and
expected world trade growth at a solid 6 to 7 percent annually.
Last year, the private capital flows to developing countries
surged to a record 245 billion U.S. dollars with foreign direct
investment exceeding 100 billion dollars for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's current projects put the East Asian GDP annual
growth at 7.6 percent from 1997 to 2006, despite the fact that the
recent currency turmoil in some Southeast Asian nations may slow
down their economic growth. For developing countries as a whole,
the GDP annual growth could reach 5.4 percent in 1997-2006, more
than twice the 2.6 percent rate in the past decade. In sub-Saharan
Africa, where some 25 countries are undertaking structural
adjustment and economic reform, recent growth has exceeded 4
percent in the past two years, about two percentage points higher
than in the previous decade. In India, home to the largest number
of the world's poor, economic growth was nearly 7 percent for the
third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
The report also underlined the expansion of cross border or
global production by multinational enterprises which is among the
most important channels through which developing countries are
becoming more integrated in the world economy. Today, some
one-fifth of the world GDP is produced by the parents and foreign
affiliates of multinational enterprises. One-fifth of world
manufacturing output is produced by multinational affiliates
alone. One-third of total world trade is conducted within
different operations of the same multinational firm. In the 1990s,
developing countries have become the fastest growing location for
cross-border production by multinationals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information Security Risks Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Information security risks
have increased and a major threat came from "computer terrorists,"
a survey found.
</P>
<P>
Covering 4,226 information services executives from 24
countries, the survey was done by the New York-based service
company Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the findings today, the company said 74 percent
of the respondents say their information security risks have risen
in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the respondents (55 percent) have expressed a
lack of confidence that their systems could withstand internal
attacks, while over a third (36 percent) lacked confidence that
their networks could weather external assault.
</P>
<P>
When identifying perceived threats to their security, the
executives put computer terrorists at the top of their lists,
followed by authorized users, former employees and unauthorized
users.
</P>
<P>
The trend toward global connectivity is creating new avenues
of opportunity for Internet terrorism, said an Ernst &AMP; Young
official who warned that monitoring the security of their networks
for breaks-ins should be an important part of their technology
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
