<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extraordinary Session of National Assembly Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The first extraordinary
session of parliament of Cameroun has ended in Yaounde on
September 8 after adopting a series of bills.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians started their work on August 26 when the
session convened.
</P>
<P>
The first bill to be passed is the validation of mandates of
seven newly elected parliamentarians who won the August 3
legislative elections re-run in the three constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The second bill tabled by the government to amend and
supplement certain provinsions of the law to lay down conditions
governing the election of the president is also adopted at a
plenary session in the absence of the Scocial Democratic Front
(SDF) party parliamentarian group and other opposition parties in
the assembly.
</P>
<P>
The bill was examined by the constitutional laws committee.
Top on the new provisions of the law, a presidential term of
office would be seven years renewable once.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect worth noting is the cfa 1500000 francs
enrolment fee each candidate will pay to run the elections.
</P>
<P>
The last bill adopted is one on private security agencies
aimed at providing legal framework to the service. The new law
sets the limits of the private security companies and lays down
sanctions for the non-respect of the rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, only Camerounians from the age of 20
and above will be authorized to establish security agencies. But
they are no longer expected to render their services in the
transportation of funds and the guarding of some state
infrastrutures, security installations and equipment. They are
not allowed to carry conventional weapons.
</P>
<P>
Now existing security agencies will have three months to abide
by the new dispositions of the law when the president of the
republic of Cameroun promulgated it into law.
</P>
<P>
With the curtain drawing over the first extraordinary session
yesterday, the next appointment for the Camerounian
parliamentarians is in November for the second ordinary session
of the national assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
