<HEADLINE> Clinton Outlines Agenda for the Rest of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Outlining a familiar agenda
for the rest of 1997, U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday
despite today's sound economy and generally peaceful climate, more
remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
Addressing students at American University, Clinton said that
he will pursue an activist agenda on several fronts, including
education, the environment and racial relations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "The news is good today. And in the face of good
news, the easiest thing to do is to rest, to take a vacation...But
complacency is not an option."
</P>
<P>
He added, "There is in fact a lot more to do...and the time to
start is now, this fall, with a series of concrete actions we can
take to cap a year of real progress for America."
</P>
<P>
White House officials had billed the speech as Clinton's effort
to better define his priorities, but he offered familiar
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reiterated calls for standardized testing in reading
and math, and the negotiating authority from Congress to craft
more trade pacts.
</P>
<P>
He referred again to protecting children from smoking and
promised to commit to specific international guidelines for
reducing greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
He pledged again support to campaign reform legislation and
publicly criticized those who oppose it, and, in racial relations,
he urged students to embrace diversity. 
</P>
