<HEADLINE> AL Urged to Discuss Growing Turkish-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Syria today expressed concern
over growing Israeli-Turkish military ties and urged the Arab
League (AL) to deal with their potential dangers, the Middle East
News Agency (MENA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Damascus will ask the AL Council's coming session slated for
September 21 to table an additional item to discuss the dangers
imposed by the Turkish-Israeli-U.S. manoeuvres to security and
peace in the region, said Eissa Darwish, Syrian ambassador in
Cairo and its permanent delegate to the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian ambassador told MENA that the Arab national
security is exposed to danger emanating from the Turkish-Israeli
military cooperation agreement that covers armament, training and
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed the military cooperation accord in
February 1996 and announced that they would stage joint naval
exercises together with the U.S. forces in the eastern
Mediterranean on November 15-25.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers provoked outcries from Arab countries,
especially Syria, which sees itself as the target of the
Turkish-Israeli alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian diplomat said Arab countries had asked Turkey to
abrogate this agreement and to work for fostering ties with Arabs
as they are linked with historical ties and joint interests.
</P>
<P>
"However, Turkey insists on maintaining its alliance with
Israel defying Arab feelings as well as those of the Turkish
people, the majority of whom strongly support setting up deep and
distinguished ties with Arab and Islamic peoples and firmly oppose
Israeli expansionist and aggressive policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Darwish made the statement a week before Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel's planned one-day visit to Egypt, which is
supposed to allay Arab concern over the Israeli-Turkish
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Turkish summit, which was originally set for May,
was postponed in the wake of the planned naval war games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0066 </DOCNO>
