<HEADLINE> UK Trade Unions Urged to Work with Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair today called for a "new trade unionism" which will see
unions working in partnership with business.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the Trade Union Congress held in the coastal
city of Brighton, he said that the unions should become involved
in making Britain and individual firms more competitive, creating
a new partnership between state, unions and employers.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister urged the unions to get involved with skills
and training and with the Labor government's Welfare to Work
program, to help the unemployed and play a central part on the
debate on the future of pensions.
</P>
<P>
"We will not go back to the days of industrial warfare, strikes
without ballots, mass and flying pickets, secondary action and all
the rest," Blair told delegates to the congress.
</P>
<P>
"You don't want it and I won't let it happen. And I will watch
very carefully to see how the culture of modern trade unionism
develops," he said. 
</P>
