<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Tourist arrivals in Cyprus in July reached 337,000,
an increase by 7.9 percent compared to that of a year before.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics released here today, 64.4
percent of the visitors came from European Union member
countries, and another 18.8 percent from the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The increase indicates a recovery of the country's tourism,
which showed a decrease of tourist arrivals in 1996.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia has emerged as the largest soft
drinks market in the Middle East region with an estimated annual
consumption of more than 1.28 billion liters, Saudi newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has also become a major supplier of canned
beverage to the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member countries
who consume annually an estimated 3.8 billion cans, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Since a new Saudi can company named United Arab Can
Manufacturing Company was opened last April, Saudi Arabia has
already exported 50 million cans to other GCC states and other
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
The company which is a joint venture with Coca Cola company of
the United States produced in three months of operation nearly 300
million cans and 500 million can ends.
</P>
<P>
It is producing a complete range of can sizes to suit the needs
of both the local and international market, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus' economy is apparently locked in a
slowing-down trend as the growth rate for 1998 was budgeted at 2
percent today.
</P>
<P>
The economy's growing pace, which was at around 5 percent in
1995, slowed down to 3 percent last year and is expected to keep
a 3.5 percent this year. A flagging tourism has been put on blame.
</P>
<P>
The budget envisages an expenditure of 1,629.9 million Cyprus
pounds (3,064.2 million U.S. dollars) and a deficit of 550 million
pounds (1,034 million dollars). The deficit represents a 41.5
percent increase over that expected for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said in a statement that large
infrastructure projects concerning water and road enjoy priorities
in the development sector of the budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
