<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-09 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Agrees Red Cross as Sole Mediator for Swap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri agreed today that the International Committee of Red Cross
(ICRC) be the sole mediator in a proposed exchange of the remains
of Israelis for Lebanese held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister agreed that ICRC should be the only contact
channel in the suggested swap, maintaining that involvement of
many sides would make things complicated, John Jack Ferzer, ICRC
representative in Lebanon, told the press following a meeting with
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese guerrillas of Hezbollah and Amal ambushed last Friday
an Israeli commando at Ansariyah village in south Lebanon, killing
12 Israeli marines and wounding four others.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah fighters offered to swap the remains of the Israelis
for 75 Lebanese held in Israeli jails, including its former
leaders Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid and Mustafa Dirani kidnaped from
their homes several years ago.
</P>
<P>
Ferzer disclosed that Israel had approached the ICRC and asked
it to transfer to the Lebanese government a message over the swap,
which he refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He said he would convey Lebanese government's reply to Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebanese reports, Israel refused to release Obeid
and Dirani at the moment, saying it was too early to talk about
it.
</P>
<P>
Asked when the mediation will take place, Ferzer said it would
need a long time, probably one week, one month, or even several
years.
</P>
<P>
The previous swap in which 45 Lebanese and the bodies of 123
Hezbollah guerrillas were exchanged for the bodies of two Israelis
took place on July 21 last year after nearly six months of
mediation by the ICRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
