<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Small Business Optimism Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New York, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Small Business Optimism
Index rose a half point in August in the United States, said
the National Federation of Independent Business (NFIB).
</P>
<P>
The Index at 104.0 represents the highest level since November
1994, it said in a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Sales figures continued to strengthen and the general sentiment
was that things would get even better over the next six months,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Owners expecting economic conditions to improve outnumbered
pessimists by eight percentage points, an even greater margin of
optimism than last month's, it added.
</P>
<P>
The August survey found a net 20 percent of small firms
planning to expand employment in the next three months, the
highest reading in the 24 year history of the NFIB.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found tighter labor market, higher wages,
modestly higher prices and strong capital spending in August.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1973, the Small Business Optimism Index covered 677
business owners this year. It was believed to be a reliable
predictor of domestic economic activity, according to the
Washington-based NFIB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Productivity Increases Quickly in 2nd quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The productivity of
American workers grew at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 2.7
percent in the second quarter, the fastest rate in three and an
half years, U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The gain was much faster than the initially estimated 0.6
percent reported last month and nearly double the 1.4 percent rate
of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Non-farm business productivity -- output per hour worked -- is
the key to how fast living standard can rise in the country.
</P>
<P>
The department reported that labor costs per unit of output --
a key ingredient in price pressures -- also slowed in the second
quarter. They rose at an annual rate of just 0.5 percent, compared
to an initial estimate of 2.4 percent and a rate of 3.1 percent in
the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
It was the slowest rate of increase in three years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it should help reassure the U.S. Federal
Reserve that wage pressures aren't accelerating even though the
unemployment rate in the U.S. is hovering just above a 24-year
low.
</P>
<P>
Economists have speculated that strong productivity has
allowed corporations to pay higher wages and earn high profits
without boosting prices.
</P>
<P>
Rapid productivity advances in the U.S. -- in excess of 3
percent a year -- supported the economic boom and low inflation of
the 1960s. But since the early 1970s, productivity growth has
averaged only about 1 percent a year. It was 1.3 percent last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
