<HEADLINE> Delegations to 15th Party Congress Arrive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The 36 delegations to the
upcoming 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) have arrived in Beijing and reported to the secretariat of
the congress this evening.
</P>
<P>
The delegations are from 31 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities, including those from the departments directly
under the central authorities, the People's Liberation Army, the
Armed Police Force, and one whose members are of Taiwanese origin.
</P>
<P>
The delegates have brought with them latest news on reform and
opening-up. They said that since the 14th Congress in 1992, the
Party Central Committee has promoted the principle of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics, furthered reform and
opening-up, and made gratifying achievements in economic
development and cultural and ethic progress.
</P>
<P>
The delegates expressed the hope that the upcoming 15th
Congress will become one that links the past with the future, and
serves as a new milestone on China's path of progress.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the socialist market economy has promoted
the development of the rural economy," said Wu Jinyin, a delegate
from central China's Henan Province, who added that active
participation by local farmers in market economy has help boost
the per capita income to 2,300 yuan last year, double the figure
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We have just initiated a new route to Australia," Yu Yan'en,
president of China Southern Airlines, said enthusiastically. Since
1992, he added, the carrier has brought in a large number of
airplanes from abroad, and has become one of chief airlines in
China, with 91 airplanes in operation and assets worth 25.9
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yongqing, a delegate from northern Anhui Province, east
China, said the colliery where he works has lost money for 12
consecutive years. "Since the 14th CPC Congress, the colliery has
actively participated in market competition. Now, its annual coal
production reaches 1.5 million tons, and it reports more than 100
million yuan in pre-tax profits each year," Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Beijing, many delegates have visited grassroots
units to hear the opinions of ordinary Party members and the
people.
</P>
<P>
Wang Dazhong, a delegate from east China Shaanxi Province who
has been a director of state-owned enterprises for 14 years,
called several meetings with staff members and Party members after
he was elected a delegate of the 15th CPC Congress.
</P>
<P>
Wang said he believes that when the state-owned enterprises are
in the red, they will wriggle out of difficulty once they are
operated in accordance with Deng Xiaoping's principle of "doing
everything on the premise of improving productivity, benefiting
national strength and people's living standards, liberating their
minds and furthering reform."
</P>
<P>
Wang Guixiang, a delegate the Women's Federation of
northermost Heilongjiang Province, said she was very proud to
attend the 15th Congress as a representative of women.
</P>
<P>
"I have made some investigations in grassroots units and
collected the opinions of my co-workers before coming to Beijing,"
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
She added, "I will voice the heartfelt wishes of women during
panel discussions at the congress."
</P>
<P>
Leg Qog, deputy secretary of the Party Committee of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, and vice-chairman of the regional government,
expressed the common aspirations of people of all ethnic groups in
Tibet when he said, "I must bring the heartfelt wishes of the more
than 90,000 Party members in Tibet Beijing, to the Party Central
Committee."
</P>
<P>
Yang Xushun, director of the Financial Department of Guizhou
province, southwest China, said he will loyally perform his duty
as a delegate so that he will live up to the expectations of the
1.08 million Party members in his province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
