<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Visits NATO Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister
Fatos Nano signed a new partnership program with the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization during his visit to the NATO
headquarters today.
</P>
<P>
Nano told the North Atlantic Council that he would extend
gratitude for the alliance's assistance in the Balkan nation's
recovery from a recent civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
Nano said that he would thank NATO member states for their
support during his country's difficult times.
</P>
<P>
"Your effort has not gone in vain," the prime minister said.
"NATO principles, expertise and operational records in Bosnia will
be born in the minds of the Albanian population and you will
hardly find an anti-NATO sensativity among the Albanians or the
country's political parties."
</P>
<P>
Nano said that his visit was to upgrade the relations between
Albania and the 15-nation alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said that within reasonable times his country that was now
seeking NATO assistance would be able to belong to those which
were among the nations which were qualified security producers and
distributors.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana described Nano's first
visit to the alliance as coming at a very important time when
Albania is recovering from political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
"Your presence here today," said the NATO chief, "is an
indication that your country is on the road of recovery."
</P>
<P>
Albania was among the first countries to sign the NATO
Partnership for Peace program in 1994 and has required NATO to
open a liaison office in its Defense Ministry to ensure permanent
assistance to its army.
</P>
<P>
A NATO delegation visited Albania last month and promised to
help the Balkan country to reconstruct its army which had been
dismantled during the country's recent riots.
</P>
<P>
NATO assistance includes recovery from the population heavy and
light weapons taken from the military depots during the riots.
</P>
