<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Clear Backing for Scottish Devolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- An overwhelming majority of
voters in Scotland gave support to Scottish devolution, according
to a poll today in Glasgow's The Herald newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The results of the poll, which came out just one day before
Thursday's Scottish devolution referendum, showed that 61 percent
of voters are in support of a Scottish Parliament, with only 20
percent opposed and 19 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
As to the question of whether they want the parliament to have
tax-raising powers, the Scots are less sure, but still there were
45 percent in favor. Those against accounted for 32 percent, with
24 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
The governing Labor Party, the Liberal Democrats and the
pro-independence Scottish National Party have been campaigning for
the same platform in support of a new Scottish Parliament with
tax-raising powers.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition Conservative Party has been urging
Scots to vote "no," saying what was at stake was the whole future
of the United Kingdom and the devolution would put Scotland on a
slippery slope to independence from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Scotland was united with England in 1707, but so far it still
keeps many of the characteristics of a nation state, with its own
legal and education systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
