<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Wu Bangguo and Zou Jiahua,
both vice-premiers and members of the Communist Party of China
Central Committee Politburo, lit a five meter-high torch here
today to mark the completion of the gas-supply project from
Shaanxi to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The project pipes gas from the Changqing gasfield in
northwestern China's Shaanxi Province to the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Wu Bangguo spoke on behalf of the central government, offering
congratulations on the completion of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project is of great importance for improving the structure
of energy consumption in the capital and the quality of living for
local residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 853-km-long pipeline, which cost 3.95
billion yuan, was started in May, 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, Beijing had long suffered from
shortage of gas.
</P>
<P>
Some 300,000 gas users, including families and institutions, are
expected to have access to the gas from Shaanxi. 
</P>
