<HEADLINE> France Firmly Rejects Taliban Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- France rejected accusations
today by the Afghan Muslim student movement Taliban that it is
providing support to the forces of another Afghan faction led by
Ahmed Shah Massud.
</P>
<P>
"France does not provide financial aid, arms, spare parts or
military materials to the protagonists (of Afghanistan)," said
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The French government knows nothing about the presence of
French engineers in Afghanistan, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
"France continues to observe strict neutrality in the crisis,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said France and its European Union partners have called on
Afghans to renounce the option of force and "engage sincerely in
the process of dialogue, which will lead to the establishment of a
government of vast union."
</P>
<P>
The chief of Taliban, Mollah Mohammed Rabbani, denounced French
engineers on Tuesday as supporting the forces of Massud by
teaching them to use weapons and pilot planes on bombing raids in
the northern city of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
He also accused France of providing financial aid, arms spare
parts "at international instances" to the opposition forces of
Afghanistan. 
