<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Economic Forum Opens in Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international forum
on global economic issues, particularly South Korea's role in the
world economy, opened here today.
</P>
<P>
In an opening address to the Korea Summit '97, South Korean
Minister of Finance and Economy Kang Kyung-shik said the
government, business and general public should strive to become
consumer-oriented with minimum bureaucratic control.
</P>
<P>
He then presented five major directions to be pursued by the
South Korean economy: re-establishment of governmental and public
sector roles in forming a consumer-oriented pattern; promotion of
fair competition and corporate transparency; enhancing flexibility
in economic and social systems; improving infrastructure for
social systems as rules and practices; and facilitating
information processing and technology innovation.
</P>
<P>
The forum, organized by the International Herald Tribune and
cosponsored by Samsung, Hyundai and Daewoo groups, is being
attended by 800 Korean and foreign dignitaries representing
political, business, academic and journalistic circles.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the South Korean government, Minister of
Trade, Industry and Energy Lim Chang-yuel said South Korea will
actively participate in additional rounds of multilateral free
trade negotiations while advancing the domestic economic systems.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of co-prosperity of developed and
developing blocs, Lim said, "Industrial countries need to take
into account the situations of industrializing countries while
strengthening technological cooperation to help the latter's
smooth industrial restructuring."
</P>
<P>
Alvin Toffler, a U.S. futurologist, who took the rostrum as a
foreign speaker, said that South Korea's current economic
difficulties are due to the fact that the country has not fully
dropped its economic structure based on the "second-wave"
industrial strategy of mass production and export drive.
</P>
<P>
"In order for South Korea to tide over these difficulties, the
nation needs to develop high value-added knowledge products that
fit the era of information, ensure labor market flexibility and
renovate educational systems," he said.
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu, vice minister of China's Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Ministry, also delivered a speech today on
China's external economic policies and Sino-South Korean economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Young-sam will deliver his keynote
speech tomorrow, followed by other government officials including
Minister of Foreign Affairs Yoo Chong-ha and Minister of
Construction and Transportation Lee Hwan-kyun.
</P>
<P>
Major South Korean business leaders, including Hyundai Group
chairman Chung Mong-koo, and Daewoo Group chairman Kim Woo-choong,
will also address the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
