<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes Iran on Pilgrims' Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Baghdad today criticized Iran
for barring its citizens from visiting Iraq by creating pretexts
on the country's reception capabilities.
</P>
<P>
All the necessary services, including security and health, for
Iranian visitors are well in place in spite of the seven-year-long
U.N. sanctions against the country, the foreign ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Iran's justifications for not permitting its citizens to visit
holy sites in Iraq are mere pretexts to deny the Iranians the
right to visit Iraq, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Gulf Department Director of the Iranian Foreign Ministry
Mohamed Jalal Fayrouznia said in a statement on September 4 that
the health and security conditions in Iraq would not afford the
normal performance of the proper rites by Iranian citizens.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on August 18 that it decided to lift a ban on
Iranian travelers to Iraq, imposed in 1980 when the Iraq-Iran War
broke out, and to allow the Iranians to visit the holy sites in
Iraq from September 4.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the government's decision was final and
irrevocable and needed no negotiations as demanded by Iran on
arrangements for its visitors.
</P>
<P>
Iran has said the Iraqi offer to admit Iranian pilgrims is
aimed at diverting attention from unresolved issues between the
two countries, such as the one of prisoners from the 1980-88
Iran-Iraqi war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
