<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Turbulence in HK, Inland China Unlikely: WB Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A currency crisis such as the
one which occurred in Thailand earlier this year will not happen
in either Hong Kong or China's interior area, a World Bank
official said here.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Hong Kong and China's interior area is very
different from that of Thailand," Austin Hu, acting chief of the
Bank's resident mission in China, said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The recent currency crisis of Thailand was largely due to
failure in economic restructuring, declining economic
competitiveness, lingering deficits in the current account,
swelling foreign-exchange debts of enterprises, and limited
foreign exchange reserves, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the Thai crisis on excessive speculative
investment in real estate and stocks, which eventually resulted in
a surge in non-performing credits and runaway foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, Hu said, the economy is stable, both the hardware
and software of the financial sector are perfect, and hard
currency reserves are strong.
</P>
<P>
All these factors, plus upbeat market attitudes, indicate that
financial turbulence will not occur in Hong Kong, the World Bank
official said.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed the possibility of currency volatility in
China, saying that the Chinese yuan is still inconvertible under
the capital account and the Chinese government exercises strict
control on borrowing from overseas.
</P>
<P>
China also has strong foreign exchange reserves, which stood at
126 billion US dollars by the end of June and may reach 135
billion US dollars by the end of this year, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, the
central bank, said earlier that China has learned a lesson from
the Thai crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We will adhere to a moderately tight monetary policy, ensure
the rational use of foreign funds, restrain from relying
excessively on foreign debts, and guard against the possibility of
a bubble economy resulting from overheated real estate and stock
markets," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has no problem in balance of payments in
foreign exchange since 64 percent of the foreign capital in the
country is direct foreign investment and 80 percent of the 120
billion US dollars in foreign debts is of long terms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
