<HEADLINE> Sound Growth of China's Defense Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China has had a key period of
reform and development in its defense industry over the past five
years, especially in developing the aerospace sector, new weapons
research, and products for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
The country launched 17 Chinese and foreign satellites in the
past five years. In the first half of this year, it sent up the
Dongfanghong-3 communications satellite, the Fengyun-2
meteorological satellite, and the Long March-3B rocket. This shows
that the aerospace technology of China has matured, said officials
with the Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for
National Defense.
</P>
<P>
China's one-billion-byte-per-second supercomputer, the Yinhe-2,
was developed in November of 1992, and the country reported
success last June with its Yinhe-3, which can do 13 billion
calculations per second. The country has the technology for even
more complicated computers, according to a source.
</P>
<P>
A number of high-tech developments have helped the
modernization of national defense andy economic expansion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth in National Defense Indsutry of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The commission also says that there has been progress in new
weapons and military equipment research and that it is being
applied in the field to improve the fighting ability of the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
The product structure of the defense industry has also
changed. The output value of civilian products has been increasing
at an annual rate of 20 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The commission says that it has large-scale enterprise groups
with more than 100 million yuan in revenues and per capita income
above 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Military enterprises now produce 60 percent of the country's
motorbikes, 26 percent of railway wagons, and nine percent of
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Sciences and technologies for national defense have been widely
applied for civil aeronautics, environmental protection,
agricultural development, and medicine, greatly helping economic,
scientific and technological and cultural development, the commission
says. 
