<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Considers Court of Final Appeal-related Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
 Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) today went through the second reading of an amended bill on
the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the legislature, Administrative Secretary Anson
Chan said that the bill proposed by the SAR government aims to
amend the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal Ordinance to improve its
provisions in respect of the constitution of the Appeal Committee.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) (No.
3) Bill 1997 is "essential" to the normal operation of the Court
of Final Appeal, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing ordinance, an Appeal Committee shall
consist of either the Chief Justice and two permanent judges
nominated by the Chief Justice, or three permanent judges
nominated by the Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
"However," Chan said, "there is no express prohibition against
bias by pre-determination in this section". "As in the case of
substantive hearings of appeals, it would be inappropriate for a
judge to sit on an Appeal Committee if he has previously rejected
the application, or if the judgment or order at issue was made by
him or by a court of which he was a member," she added.
</P>
<P>
As the proposed exclusion from the Appeal Committee of judges
who have had a previous involvement with the case may mean that
there are insufficient permanent judges to sit on that committee,
the amended bill provides that where a sufficient number of
permanent judges is not available for any cause to sit on the
Appeal Committee, the Chief Justice shall nominate a non-permanent
Hong Kong judge to sit in place of a permanent judge, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
The bill also aims to clear doubts as to the powers of the
Appeal Committee, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The PLC members also discussed a number of issues concerning
the forthcoming legislative elections, housing, designation of
Teachers' Day and women's care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
