<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Stick to One-China Policy: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said today Australia will stick to one-China
policy and urged other Western countries to deal with China on
human rights issue in a constructive way.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to our one-China policy ... and under our
one-China policy, which goes back to 1972, we don't recognize
Taiwan as a separate political entity," Downer told the
Asia-Australia Institute in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"They (China) of course understand that we are going to have
economic contacts with Taiwan," the foreign minister was quoted by
the Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Participating in a discussion organized by the institute on
"How should Australia's foreign policy-makers deal with China's
growing influence", the foreign minister rejected the assertion
that China might splinter into separate entities.
</P>
<P>
"To understand China includes understanding their absolute
determination to remain a united country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The sensitivity about Taiwan, and for that matter Tibet, is
born very much out of concern for the fragmentation of China," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On human rights issue, Downer urged other Western countries to
follow Australia's suit in dealing with China in a constructive
way.
</P>
<P>
Australia has been the first Western country that has conducted
a dialogue on human rights with China recently on the basis of
mutual respect and in a constructive way.
</P>
<P>
Grabbing headlines by criticizing China's record on human
rights had proven unproductive, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Downer said that since the recent handover of power in Hong
Kong, the government was receiving message of "business as usual"
from Australian firms operating there.
</P>
<P>
He told the meeting at the State Library of New South Wales
that for China, as for Australia, a stable and peaceful region
provided that necessary climate for continued growth in trade and
economic activity generally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
