<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kuala Lumpur Stock Shares Face Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Wu Dingbao)
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Shares on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) suffered from a setback today on
profit-taking after a sharp rebound for three successive days.
</P>
<P>
At the close today, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index (CI)
fell 25.67 points or by 2.88 percent to 863.08, the all-share Emas
index dropped 6.20 points to 244.96, the Industrial Index was
60.31 points lower at 1,746.89 while the Second Board Index lost
4.46 points to 451.36.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE started recovery on September 5 when the benchmark CI,
which once retreated to 675.15 low on persistent selling pressure
by foreign investors, surged 90.47 points or 12.37 percent to
close at 821.59 last week following the aggressive buying by local
funds.
</P>
<P>
It continued its upward trend during the following two days
with the CI ending at 879.71 points on September 8 and closing at
888.75 points Tuesday respectively.
</P>
<P>
The recovery was seen to be triggered by Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad's announcement on September 4 of the
lifting of designated securities status on the 100-stock index
components and of the deferment in the implementation of several
projects, which analysts said restored confidence in market
players.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Mahathir also announced the setting-up of a 60-billion
ringgit (20.69 billion U.S. dollars) fund, with the government
itself advancing 30 billion ringgit (10.34 billion dollars)
towards the fund, to shore up the bourse.
</P>
<P>
A market analyst said today, "There is no reason not to sell as
prices had gone up sharply in the past few days." And foreign
funds were also selling blue chips, he added.
</P>
<P>
Today, losers thumped gainers by 612 to 124 while 71 counters
were unchanged and 78 untraded, with total turnover being 325.633
million shares worth 1.716 billion ringgit (about 591.7 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board volume dropped to 267.923 million shares worth
1.216 billion ringgit (about 419.3 million U.S. dollars) from
511.910 million shares valued at 2.197 billion ringgit (about
757.5 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday. The second board turnover was
57.710 million shares worth 500.747 million ringgit (about 172.6
million U.S. dollars) against Tuesday's 88.458 million shares
valued at 722.612 million ringgit (about 249.1 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Direct business deals were reduced to 15.692 million shares
worth 911.094 million ringgit (about 314.1 million U.S. dollars)
against Tuesday's 34.280 million shares valued at 220.267 million
ringgit (about 75.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the analysts maintained that there should not be
anymore "panicking" as the market sentiment had strengthened with
the above measures taken by the government restoring confidence in
market players.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some recent government forecasts, such as this year's
current account deficit at 5.2 percent from 5.5 percent of Gross
National Products and Gross Domestic Product growth at over 8
percent this financial year, also helped restore confidence in
market players.
</P>
<P>
They are confident that the 900-level would be breached later
this week or next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
