<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dates for Pak-Indian Talks Not Confirmed: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is still awaiting
a response from India about the third round of foreign secretary
level talks between the two countries, a Foreign Office spokesman
said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are still awaiting the response from India," the spokesman
said when referring to an Indian report that talks will begin in
New Delhi from September 15.
</P>
<P>
"We have not received anything on it yet," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The last round of foreign secretary level talks between
Pakistan and India was held here in June.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides agreed to set up working groups
to resolve all outstanding issues including Kashmir between the
two countries. They also agreed to resume their talks some time
this month in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed Tuesday expressed
his hope that Pakistan will not be forced out of the process of
dialogue for resolving outstanding issues including the core issue
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
While stressing Pakistan's keen desire for the dialogue with
India, he said the Kashmir issue is a stumbling block between the
two countries for having good neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have resumed their foreign secretary level
talks in March in New Delhi after a suspense of more than three
years. The talks had broken down in January 1994 due to their
differences on the Kashmir issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
