<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Reportedly Enter Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Islamic Taliban
forces today have reportedly entered the main opposition
stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Kabul,
Pakistan Television (PTV) reported.
</P>
<P>
Armed clashes have erupted as the Taliban fighters entered this
morning the Afghanistan's second largest city, stronghold of
anti-Taliban strongman Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik, and they were
joined by some defected local commanders, PTV quoted a report by
private Afghan Islamic Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting was continuing to rage at some parts of the
city between Taliban fighters and forces loyal to Malik, whose
brief alliance with Taliban has led the student militia to a
humiliating defeat in May in northern Afghanistan, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
However, no independent confirmation of the report was
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
As conflicting reports kept pouring in here from Afghanistan,
no one knows exactly how close the Taliban positions from
Mazar-e-Sharif, the only major Afghan city not in Taliban's hand.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports of an apparent internal coup against Malik met
with a strong denial from a spokesman for the ousted Afghan
government, who dismissed the information as "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also denied the report that General Malik has
already fled abroad from Mazar-e-Sharif, saying "these are just
rumors, the alliance forces are in full control of the situation."
</P>
<P>
Malik, who is now allied with forces led by Afghanistan's
former military chief Ahmad Masood and Shiite faction
Hezb-e-Wahdat, took control of Mazar-e-Sharif late May after
turning against this former boss Rashid Dostum who had been the
main ethnic Uzbek commander.
</P>
<P>
He defected to the Taliban side on May 19, helping the
hard-line Islamic militia sweep across key northern provinces and
take Mazar-e-Sharif. But he then turned on his new allies after
disagreements surfaced over power-sharing and forced the Taliban
out of the city.
</P>
<P>
The alliance factions now defending Mazar-e-Sharif are
Hezb-e-Wadhat, another Shiite group Harakat-e-Islami and former
president Burhanuddin Rabbani's Jamiat-e-Islami.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control about two-thirds of the Afghan
territory and the capital of Kabul, have vowed to impose a strict
Islamic rule in the war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
