<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Forges Action Plan to Spur Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
today came up with an 11-point action plan to save its economy
which has slowed down after being hit by a protracted currency
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The strategies were drawn during a joint meeting of the
departments of trade and industry, finance, agriculture, and the
National Economic and Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary Cesar Bautista said among the 11 proposals, the
development of the country's infrastructure was deemed crucial in
stimulating economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include cutting transaction costs in banks,
reducing government bureaucracy, improving trade balance to
increase foreign reserves, increasing domestic savings and
ensuring sustainable agriculture growth.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said these action plans can be implemented in the
"meantime" to mitigate the impact of the peso depreciation and
rising interest rate on the growth of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the business sector believes that the Philippines can
be better off after this temporary currency turmoil, compared with
its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine economy, which has been viewed as a new tiger
economy, showed signs of slowdown during the first half of this
year. In the first semester, the country recorded a
lower-than-expected 5.9 percent gross national product growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
Because of the current currency turmoil and high interest
rates, the economy is expected to further slow down in the second
half, making the government difficult to meet growth targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
