<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import Corn, Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today approved the importation of 300,000 tons of corn to
prevent a corn shortage in the country due to the effects of the
coming El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
This volume of corn, to be imported at a 35 percent low tariff,
is expected to ease a projected severe corn shortage in 1997-98
crop year.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department estimated there will be a
1.4-million-ton corn shortage in this crop year because of an
expected fall in local corn production caused by El Nino-triggered
severe drought.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, a kind of weather phenomenon which can cause
catastrophic effects including storm and drought, is expected to
hit the Philippines in the last quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Ramos today also endorsed the importation of 29,000 tons of
frozen beef to meet the increasing demand for beef by the domestic
meat processing industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
