<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Central Bank in Structural Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
(RBZ) today said it has embarked on a restructuring exercise to
streamline its management and service delivery structures with a
view to improving efficiency and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, under which the bank would install a new
information technology system, was intended to re-position the
central bank to meet the ever-growing needs of an economy that
has undergone massive changes over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for the bank said the changes transformed the
functions and role of the central bank from one of being an
administrator to that of supervising, facilitating and
monitoring, thereby allowing the RBZ to play a more
interventionist role in the market.
</P>
<P>
''This exercise should result in new management and service
delivery cost structures and a culture that are both relevant and
responsive to the changing needs of the country,'' the
spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
A committee had been created to spearhead the process and was
expected to complete its work before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Economic changes since 1991, when the country embarked on a
donor-backed reform program, have seen the opening of the economy
and the removal of most controls.
</P>
<P>
Among the changes was the relaxation of exchange controls and
the liberalization of the marketing of agricultural products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
