<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Remains Hesitant About Attending Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Oman has not yet decided to
attend the fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic
Conference, which is scheduled to be held in the Qatari capital of
Doha in November, an Omani minister of state said today.
</P>
<P>
Oman is awaiting a joint stand by most of other Arab states
toward the conference and Oman will be in keeping with it, said
Oman's Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Ben-Alawi in
the Omani capital of Muscat.
</P>
<P>
"Oman will be in keeping with other Arab states who have not
made decisions to attend the conference with regard to the current
situation in the Middle East process," he told the Omani news
agency.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
process, some Arab countries such as Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Syria and Lebanon have decided to boycott the November
conference which Israel is expected to be invited.
</P>
<P>
However, most of other Arab countries adopt a wait-and-see
stand and await an Arab League foreign ministers' meeting in
Cairo on September 20-21.
</P>
<P>
Qatar remains determined to host the conference. Qatari
officials said Qatar is going ahead with preparations for
the conference and invitations will be sent out at the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
The conference, launched in 1994 and held last year in Egypt,
is traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel and their major
trade partners in the industrialized world. Israel has attended
all the three previous ones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
