<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Labs, Chinese University Opens First Joint Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Bell Laboratories and the
Shanghai Jiaotong University (SJU), a renowned institution of
higher learning in China, today declared the opening here of a
joint lab for communications and network development.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, the initial research of the lab
will focus on technology for computer processing of the Chinese
language.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the lab's opening, the first group of Chinese
scientists will attend a six-month training in the US state of New
Jersey, where the Bell headquarters is located.
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony of the joint lab were Dr. Tse
Lin (Jack) Wang, who leads Bell Labs' research and development
efforts in China, and Prof. Xie Shengwu, president of the Shanghai
Jiaotong University.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts considered that only by strengthening technical
transfer and exchanges with Chinese partners could foreign telecom
companies gain a better position in China's ever-intensifying
telecom competition.
</P>
<P>
Bell Labs has given birth to such innovations as the
transistor, laser, digital computer, communications satellite,
solar energy battery and cellular telephone that have had
significant impact on the 20th century's technological development.
</P>
<P>
As the research and development arm of Lucent Technologies, a
world telecommunications systems and technology leader, Bell Labs
now has bases in 17 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
