<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Issue Benchmark Bond to Support Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
is to issue next week its benchmark bonds with a tenure of three
years to be used to support the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
(KLSE) which came under severe selling pressure recently.
</P>
<P>
The bonds, to be issued by Khazanah Nasional Bhd, the
government's investment arm, were launched here by Malaysian
Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim tonight at a dinner hosted by
the Association of Banks in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The bonds with the first issue worth one billion ringgit (about
345 million U.S. dollars) on September 18, 1997, will be opened
for tender on State Bank's Fully Automated System for Tendering
(FAST) from September 11, 1997, Khazanah Nasional said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The bonds, as announced by Malaysia Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad last week, will be used as part of a 60 billion ringgit
(about 20.69 billion U.S. dollars) fund to support the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the Khazanah benchmark bond would also, in
time, assist in the development of bond futures and options to add
breadth to the financial derivatives market, it said.
</P>
<P>
"And in line with the government's efforts to encourage greater
savings among the public, unit trust companies and banking
institutions would now be able to offer additional investment
instruments in the form of bond funds and bond-related savings
schemes," Khazanah Nasional said.
</P>
<P>
Khazanah Nasional, wholly-owned by the Ministry of Finance
(Incorporated) which manages the government's assets to optimize
returns, pledged that it would be well placed to ensure that the
proceeds of the benchmark issues are prudently reinvested so as to
uphold and improve the risk rating of Khazanah Nasional at all
times.
</P>
<P>
Among the main features of the Khazanah benchmark bond issuance
program, is that it would be a zero-coupon based on the concept of
murabahah, fully guaranteed by the government, and would be issued
on a quarterly basis with maturities of three, five, seven and 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the issue size would not be less than 500 million
ringgit (about 172 million U.S. dollars) per issue and that it
would not qualify for liquid assets status but they would be
included in determining the volume of trading for purposes of
netting off against eligible liability base.
</P>
<P>
There would be competitive bidding on the basis of price
through the Principal Dealers on State Bank's FAST and would be
traded on the Scripless Securities Trading System (SSTS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
