<HEADLINE> DPRK Soldier to Be Repatriated Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A soldier from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), who drifted along a river to
South Korea, will be repatriated soon, the Defense Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman said Cho Kang-gon, 21, could be sent home
as early as tomorrow via the truce village of Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
Cho, found on the small island of Kyodong-do in the Yellow Sea
on August 25, said he had accidentally fallen from a small boat
into the Yesong River, and then requested to be sent home.
</P>
<P>
In the past, South Korea has on several occasions repatriated
DPRK soldiers who had accidentally drifted into southern waters.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK is also expected to repatriate through Panmunjom on
Friday the remains of a U.S. soldier killed during the Korean War
(1950-53), said a U.S. Army spokesman stationed in South Korea
today.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation will be the second this year. Pyongyang handed
over the remains of four American soldiers to U.S. forces on
August 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
