<HEADLINE> General Course of Sino-Japanese Relations Sound: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today that the general course of Sino-Japanese relations
has always been sound because of the joints efforts from both
sides.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) Central Committee, met this afternoon with the ninth
Japanese delegation of the "Great Wall" program to come to China.
The program was founded nine years ago with an objective of
promoting Sino-Japanese, non-governmental friendly exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which arrived here earlier today, was led by
former Japanese Prime Minister Kaifu Toshiki and included dozens
of parliament members from the New Frontier Party.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the present good relationship, which was hard-won,
reflects the painstaking efforts from statesmen of the former
generations and the insightful personnel of both countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the present visit in of great significance in
that the delegation comes at a time when both countries are
celebrating the 25th anniversary of the normalization of their
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
The president also spoke highly of Toshiki's efforts in
promoting bilateral relations, calling him an "old friend" of
China. The Chinese people will never forget those old friends who
have made positive efforts for the advancement of Sino-Japanese
ties, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The successful implementation of the "Great Wall" program
reflects the solid basis of bilateral relations, and demonstrates
the good wishes of both sides to expand their friendly
cooperation, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
During the past nine years, since the start of the "Great Wall"
program, which is non-governmental, Japan has sent more than 100
parliament members to China.
</P>
<P>
Toshiki said that the improvement of Japan-China relations is
of importance not only to Japan but also to the maintenance of
peace and stability in Asia and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He said he will spare no efforts to increase dialogue and
expand common understanding between the two countries through
different means and to actively promote the contacts between the
younger statesmen in a bid to pass on the friendship from
generation to generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
