<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enjoy More Latitude in Choosing Careers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Ding Hongbo has worked as a
salesman and a legal affairs consultant at three different firms
since graduating from Beijing University with a bachelor's degree
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Now, the 27-year-old Beijing resident wants to get a master's
degree in order to apply for his fourth job: a university law
teacher.
</P>
<P>
"I've come to find that I'm fit for this profession much more
than the former ones, though I did work well at those firms," said
Ding, who is planning to enroll in the graduate school at the
Chinese University of Political Science and Law next summer.
</P>
<P>
Ding's experience in hunting and switching jobs reflects a
rising trend among young people in China, who have more latitude
in choosing their own careers than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"Market economy creates opportunities, so people can make more
choices to realize individual values by seeking jobs that are
fit for them," said economist Fan Gang.
</P>
<P>
Only ten years ago, zigzagging down the career path was
unimaginable in China.
</P>
<P>
Under the traditional planned economy structure, most Chinese
people's professions were assigned by the country, and most people
spent their whole life at one job, Fan said.
</P>
<P>
"People were so deeply restricted by the outdated way of
thinking that in the mid-1980s, few people dared to find a new job
at our center," said Zhang Yuquan, head of the Beijing Personnel
Service Center.
</P>
<P>
But his business grew several times over, especially after the
Communist Party of China outlined the establishment of a socialist
market economic structure at its 14th National Congress in
1992. The center has become the largest personnel market in
Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enjoy More Latitude in Choosing Careers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fan attributed the great change to the socialist market economy
that is being established in China following the country's
decade-long reform and opening-up efforts.
</P>
<P>
The 43-year-old economist himself gave up a job at the official
Economic Research Institute under the Chinese Academy of Social
Science two years ago to work at the non-governmental China Reform
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"More and more people and businesses, even government organs,
are realizing how important a flow of trained personnel is to the
development of not only individuals, but also the country," Zhang
Yuquan stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The country's personnel affairs departments have published a
series of policies to encourage personnel flow since 1992, and the
general public is also becoming more aware of it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Personnel show that about 5.71
million people applied for jobs at personnel markets nationwide in
1995, and the figure jumped to 10.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by Horizon Market Survey and
Analysis Company in five major Chinese cities in 1996, people
under the age of 35 have switched jobs for an average of 1.11
times in the past five years, while those over 35 changed an
average 1.07 times.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 percent of those who took different jobs said they
were satisfied with their new occupations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
