<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Scale Down Economic Growth Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
revise downward its growth targets for 1997 due to high interest
rates and a weak currency, President Fidel Ramos confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, Ramos said there will be a
"moderate" revise on this year's economic growth targets, and the
country's economic managers are now computing the new targets.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos, who has been confident that the economy will meet
its ambitious growth target of 7 to 8 percent, insisted there will
be no "slump" in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo and
Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said it would be
difficult to achieve the original growth targets this year.
</P>
<P>
This year, the gross national product (GNP) growth target is
set between 7 and 8 percent while the gross domestic product (GDP)
growth is targeted at 6.3 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the GNP posted a
lower-than-expected growth of 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the GNP target could be met unless it records an
impossible 8.3 percent growth during the second half this year.
They predicted a further slowdown in the economy in the second
half. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
