<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santer Confident of Euro Timetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- European Commission President
Jacques Santer today stressed that there is no return from the
movement toward the European single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
"I will not make apologies for saying it again," said Santer,
"that the single currency will be a reality on January 1, 1999,
and there will a substantial number of member states taking part
right from the beginning."
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the end is in sight and it is
not the time to frighten off the public about the solidity of the
new currency.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that the EU confidence and conviction will not be
put off by speculation, pessimism or even hostility.
</P>
<P>
"We have to concentrate our efforts on just one thing and that
is to deliver," said the commission president who cited as proof
that all the conditions have been fulfilled and all the necessary
elements are in place to be successful in meeting the challenge.
</P>
<P>
All the major decisions have been made except for the decision
on who will be in the first wave of joining the single currency,
said the commission president.
</P>
<P>
"In the spring of 1998, in April or May, this decision will be
taken as well," Santer added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that spring was chosen as only by then will the
real financial and economic data of EU countries become available.
</P>
<P>
There is in the European Council a political will, added
Santer, to respect the deadline and criteria set for the
inauguration of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Two of the five criteria set in the 1992 Maastricht Treaty are
that the budget deficit of an applicant country cannot exceed 3
percent of its annual gross domestic product while its debt cannot
exceed 60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Right now, only Luxembourg has met both criteria while Ireland,
the Netherlands and Denmark are closing gap to meeting the
criteria.
</P>
<P>
Santer, however, promised that the negotiation for joining the
single currency will include and not exclude countries though
negotiation is expected to begin with a limited number of
countries.
</P>
<P>
When asked if a return from the materialization of euro is now
legally and technically impossible, Santer said that the EU has
reached an irreversible point on the route toward the euro and all
the indicators are moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that on the first of January 1999 we shall have the
euro on the basis of the convergence of the criteria as defined by
the Maastricht Treaty with a substantive number of member states
being involved," Santer concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
