<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Deficit-GDP Ratio to Decline Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Italy's prospects for bringing
its deficit-gross domestic product (GDP) ratio under control are
much better than those of Germany and France, a report by the
International Monetary Fund (IFM) said today.
</P>
<P>
The deficit-GDP ratios of Italy, Germany and France are all
slightly above the 3 percent parameter mandated by the Masstricht
Treaty for entry into the European single currency system in 1999,
but Italy will achieve the most in lowering the ratio, the IMF's
World Economic Outlook said.
</P>
<P>
Italy's deficit-GDP ratio is estimated to stand at 3.2 percent
by the end of 1997, compared with 3.1 percent in Germany, said the
report, which will be released next week at the IMF's annual
meeting in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It says that Italy's deficit-GDP ratio is expected to drop to 3
percent in 1998, compared with Germany's 2.9 percent and France's
3.2 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The report said Italy will enjoy a much stronger growth -- 1.2
percent of the GDP -- than expected by the end of this year, with
the inflation rate of 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the Italian economy will recover since the
government has made serious efforts to reform the fiscal system
and curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
However, unemployment in Italy, Germany and France, predicted
to be 12.2 percent, 12.6 percent and 11.3 percent respectively in
1997, remains a serious problem. The three countries have the
highest jobless rates among the G-7, ahead of Japan's 3.5 percent,
the United States' 5.1 percent, Britain's 5.8 percent and Canada's
9.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
