<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: China Bids Farewell to Insufficient Supply of Goods (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, September 10 (Xinhua) -- "Fortnightly Chat", China's
largest circulated publication, recently carried a commentary on
China's economic success putting an end to the nation's
decades-long short supply of goods.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, a famous Hungarian Economist rocked the world with a
prediction that insufficient supplies of goods were an ineluctable
derivative of socialism. His prediction has failed to apply to
today's China, a country in which shops are filled with wide
variety of goods, and where short supplies remain only in the
memory of the people.
</P>
<P>
The commentary noted that a rapidly developing economy has
enabled Chinese to bid farewell to destitution resulting from a
short supply of goods, a headache which haunted the country for
almost three decades.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the 1980s, people used coupons to purchase a kilogram
of flour or a piece of cloth. Visiting foreigners humorously
labeled China as a sea of blue and grey, a reference to the
clothing worn by people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
It was true that China was far from extricating itself from
supply shortages under the former planned economic systems.
</P>
<P>
Most Chinese now wear colorful stylish clothing. Estimates
indicate that China's 1996 aggregate sales for clothing topped 320
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that less than two decades of reform and
opening have enabled the Chinese people to enjoy the blessings of
a bumper supply of merchandise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Meets Australian Defense Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- General Chi Haotian,
vice-chairman of the Chinese Central Military Commission and
