<HEADLINE> Program to Help Blind Tibetans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 blind people in
the Tibet Autonomous Region are expected to regain their eyesight
thanks to a special medical program which will be launched soon.
</P>
<P>
The program, launched jointly by the China Red Cross
Foundation, the China Central Television Station and the Guangming
Enterprise Group, a major Chinese furniture manufacturer, will
organize groups of volunteer opthalmologists to perform free
cataract surgery on about 5,000 blind Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held by the organizers today to see off the
first group of volunteers, who are leaving for Tibet on
Friday. The volunteers will perform 600 surgical procedures
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
At least 5,000 Tibetans have lost their eyesight due to
cataract caused by excessive exposure to the strong ultraviolet
rays characteristic in the high altitude region. Limited local
medical conditions and financial resources prevented cataract
sufferers from receiving timely treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: China Bids Farewell to Insufficient Supply of Goods (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1996, China reaped a record 490 million ton grain harvest.
</P>
<P>
The most significant improvement centers on the dramatic change
in the living standards of the Chinese people. China invested 1.15
trillion yuan in housing construction in cities between 1991-1996,
with the average per capita living space rising to 8.47 sq.m. in
1996, a substantial rise of 4.6 sq.m. when compared to
1980. Nearly half of all farmers moved into new houses.
</P>
<P>
Modern appliances, such as stereos, video-cameras, telephones,
air-conditioners and mobile phones are entering ordinary family
homes at at a startling rate. Today, every 100 households in urban
China owns 70 refrigerators, 90 washing machines and 93.5 color
TVs.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said the country has also recorded rapid
progress in infrastructure development, an area once bottlenecked
economic development. China currently ranks second in the world in
power generation, with the nation's annual steel production
exceeding 100 million tons, and coal production of well over 300
million tons setting a new world record. Highways cover the
country, and civil aviation has witnessed speedy development.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that achievements should be attributed to
the Communist Party of China which has acted in accordance with
Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics and has perfected the route of reform and
opening. The approach well fits China's unique situation.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidance of the CPC, according to the commentary,
china has extricated itself from the shackles of the planned
economy and shifted to market economy in attempt to pursue the
full development of productive forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Warns Bosnians Against Boycotting Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- France today warned Bosnian
Croats and Serbs against boycotting the municipal elections due to
be held in Bosnia on September 13-14.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said today
that France will withdraw its aid for the Bosnian cities which
boycott the election.
</P>
<P>
"We will be in favor of a freeze of all new aid projects or
assistance destinated for the cities which refuse to play the game
of democracy and thus are responsible for the blocking of the
functioning of the institutions (of the country)," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France "categorically" rejects the proposal
to delay the holding of the municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) and the Serbian Democratic
Party (SDS) have asked for a delay of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Originally scheduled for September 1996, the elections have
already been delayed four times.
</P>
<P>
"This proximity polling makes up an essential step of the peace
process and offers a new chance to the process of democratization
in Bosnia-Herzegovina," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is in the interests of Bosnians themselves to
cooperate in good faith in applying the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
is in charge of supervising the elections, which will cost 14
million U.S. dollars in preparation work and will draw 2,500
international observers, including 207 French observers, said the
spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: China Bids Farewell to Insufficient Supply of Goods(3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We have adhered to economic development based on multiple forms
of ownership which centers primarily on public ownership. Efforts
to revitalize the national economy have been accompanied by the
rapid growth of the nonstate sector. For example, despite holding
only 20 percent of total assets, township enterprises have
produced nearly half of the nation's total industrial value-added,
profits and output value.
</P>
<P>
We have strived to deepen the country's opening over the past
decade, with total imports and exports hitting 290 billion US
dollars in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
According to the commentary, these facts alone eloquently speak
for the remarkable steps we have taken over the past two decades,
especially since 1992.
</P>
<P>
China serves as an inspiring example for developing countries
around the world, according to Secretary General of the United
Nations, Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The farewell to inadequate supply marks the beginning of a new
era which will emphasize economic restructuring and high quality
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The days when factories exhibited little interest in whether or
not their products were sold are long gone. Today, they are faced
with heated struggles to lure consumers. "Everything we do should
center on the market," according to the manager of a major Chinese
washing-machine manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
It is essential to make breakthroughs in the reform of
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We should make every effort to explore effective patterns of
public ownership, and modes of management and forms of
organizations which reflect the law of socialized production",
according to Chinese President Jiang Zemin. Jiang made the
comments in an important speech delivered on May 29 at the Party
School of the CPC Central Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
