<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA to Take no Act over Anderlecht Bribes Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- UEFA will take no action over
an bribe scandal involving Anderlecht whose former chairman
admitted they paid a 30,000 U.S. dollars bribe to the referee of a
1984 UEFA Cup match against Nottingham Forest.
</P>
<P>
UEFA spokesman Frits Ahlstrom said UEFA had decided not to seek
sanctions against the club on the basis of a ten-year statute of
limitations.
</P>
<P>
Anderlecht chairman Roger Vaden Stock admitted last week his
father Constant, the club's chairman, had paid the Spanish
refereee, Guruceta Muro, "a loan" of one million francs (30,000
U.S. dollars) the day after the second leg of the tie.
</P>
<P>
Anderlecht won the match 3-0 for a 3-2 aggregate victory but
only after a Forest goal, which television replays showed to have
been legitimate, was disallowed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
