<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Finance Minister Pushes For New Economic Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram said today that India's outdated laws had inhibited
the country's economic growth and needed drastic overhaul.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a three-day economic editors' conference here
organized by the Press Information Bureau, the finance minister
said, "We cannot have a 21st century economic superstructure in
the country with outdated laws."
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the legislation, such as those relating to
the companies or income tax, were drafted in the 1940s or 1950s.
There was an urgent need to overhaul them now, especially in the
wake of economic liberalization. At least five new legislation
needed to be passed urgently by the parliament to keep
liberalization on track and help sustain GDP growth rate of 7
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said the government would introduce the
amended Income Tax Bill in the winter session of the parliament
and the Sick Industries Companies' Act had been referred to a
standing committee.
</P>
<P>
The Money Laundering Bill would be ready in a few days and it
would be brought before the parliament along with the Foreign
Exchange Management Act. The Companies Bill was also being
referred to a standing committee, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would try to get these legislation adopted
before the end of next March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
