<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
finished lower today as market participants focused their
attention on the employment figures to be released tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The markets are watching for the August labor force data to be
released by the Australian Bureau of Statistics, which will give
them a clearer picture on where official interest rates are
headed.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts for the unempolyment rate center on 8.6 percent with
expectations ranging from 8.5 to 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 72.70 U.S. cents down from
72.90 late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The jobs figures are expected to show a return to employment
growth, economists said, adding that a strong outcome would cement
a view that an interest rate cut is on hold for the time being.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia lowered the official cash rate on
July 30 to 5.0 percent, it was the fifth cut since July last year,
aimed at spurring on Australia's sluggish growth.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates today, the Australian dollar ended at 86.80
from 86.53 against yen and at 1.3180 from 1.3161 against mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
