<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes Measures to Avoid Monetary Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has taken measures to
prevent its economy from being affected by the monetary crisis
that has been damaging the economies of some countries in
Southeast Asia for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
A four-point plan has been recommended by State Bank
Director-General Cao Si Kiem, according to today's "Vietnam News."
</P>
<P>
The measures would help stem imports of unnecessary foreign
goods and promote exports with prompt and flexible banking and
incentive policies.
</P>
<P>
They include encouraging exporters and producers to cooperate
more closely, putting tighter controls on imports and smuggling,
tightening budgetary provisions and putting the commercial banking
system on a sounder financial footing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Vietnamese government has managed to increase
foreign reserves and to boost domestic production.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese officials said the prime reason for Vietnam not
being affected directly by the current regional financial crisis
was that the country had not really opened up its financial market
to a regional setting and that national controls over foreign
currency exchange remained very strict.
</P>
<P>
However, the officials said that some indirect impact could
occur.
</P>
<P>
The main worry was about the higher competitive edge of imports
from Thailand and other neighboring nations against domestic
products in Vietnam's market.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports to these countries would be challenged by
low-priced goods with devalued Thai baht and other foreign
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The loss of competitive edge would prompt more demand for hard
currency in Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
