<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abacha Won't Succeed Himself, Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The military administrator of
Ogun State in west Nigeria has turned down the country-wide
speculation that Head of State General Abacha is planning to
succeed himself as civilian president.
</P>
<P>
Wing Commander Sam Ewang disclosed on Tuesday that General
Abacha had personnaly assured him he had no such ambition to
become a president at the end of the current transition program
next year.
</P>
<P>
"The head of state has never said he is going to succeed
himself," the commander said, quoted by the Nigerian Tribune
today.
</P>
<P>
"I have met the head of state personally...and moreover he has
told me that he will hand over the reins of power to a
democratically elected government come October 1998, and not to
succeed himself" he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to Nigerians to stop spreading the rumor or
speculation as it is counter-productive.
</P>
<P>
Ewang's words came after two of his colleagues had said they
would support the presidency of Abacha, who is reported to be
seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the military administrator of Kano State in north
Nigeria, Colonel Dominic Oneya, asserted Abacha was free to
aspire to the presidency of the nation.
</P>
<P>
"If he desires to contest any elective office, I will give him
my support being a citizen of Kano," Oneya said.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Mohammed Marwa, military administrator of Lagos State,
expressed the same view a month ago.
</P>
<P>
They are currently the only two out of the 36 administrators
that have declared support to Abacha's candidancy if he chooses
to contest in next year's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
A recent research done by scholars from a group of Nigerian
universities in the north, where almost all high-ranking military
officers come from, claimed that 72 percent of Nigerians support
Abacha's presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
