<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Senior Officials on Rupee-U.S. dollar Band </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 10 (Xinhua)-- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram said today that no decision had been taken on fixing a
band in which the rupee could move freely against U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the three-day economic editors' conference here, the
finance minister said that the rupee-dollar band was one of the
ideas thrown up by the Tarapre Committee on capital account
convertibility, which was still being studied and no decision on
it had been made by the government.
</P>
<P>
India's currency rupee has for the last one month been
fluctuating wildly against the U.S. dollar in volatile trading in
the foreign exchange markets in Mumbai (Bombay), forcing the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to pump in more than 600 million U.S.
dollars during the period to arrest the slump of rupee. RBI
governor today declared the bank's intention to continue
intervention in the foreign exchange markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Dr. Montek Singh Ahluwalia said here today
that the exchange rate would be determined by the market and RBI
would intervene only to correct aberrations.
</P>
<P>
"We are neither operating on a fixed exchange rate system nor
do we have a real effective exchange rate target. But RBI will
intervene when rupee fluctuates beyond the underlying
fundamentals," he told the economic editors' conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
