<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Sixth Largest City Group in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has become a major
part of a city group on the Yangtze River Delta that is similar to
London, Paris, Chicago, New York, and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The delta is one of China's most developed areas, covering a
50,000-sq.km. area with over 80 million people. These are only one
percent and six percent of China's total, respectively, but the
area's GDP accounts for a fifth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Shanghai, Wuxi, Yangzhou, Changzhou, Zhenjiang,
and Ningbo are industrial bases with large chemical, electronics,
textile, machinery, and metallurgical industries. Shanghai is
China's largest port and Ningbo is the deepest.
</P>
<P>
The area is also a major grain producer and a leader in
township and village-based industries that have made workers out
of millions of farmers. In recent years, it has also become a
pilot area for the country's economic reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
It has 55,000 overseas-funded firms and half of the world's top
100 companies have branches here. There are also 17 state-approved
economic and technological development zones and two bonded zones.
</P>
<P>
All major cities in the area have ports that are open to
foreign vessels. There are navigations by water and air to link
the area with more than 100 countries and regions. In the 21st
century, the world will focus on Asia, while Asia focuses on China
and China on the Yangtze River Delta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dinosaur Eggs Discovered in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Local people and
archaeologists have discovered 363 fossilized dinosaur eggs in
Heyuan City in south China's Guangdong province in about past two
years.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Zikui, an expert on dinosaur egg research at the Institute
of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology of the Chinese
Academy of Science, says he believes they date back more than 65
million years and predicts that skeletal fossils may be unearthed
in the area.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that Heyuan ranks second in China in number
of discovered fossilized dinosaur eggs, after Xishan Prefecture in
Henan province.
</P>
<P>
On March 4, 1996, two round "stone eggs" were confirmed by
archaeologists in the area as being dinosaur egg fossils.
</P>
<P>
Huang Dong, head of the Heyuan Museum, says the local
government is interested in the discovery and has listed the area
as a protected one, with all projects to be built in the area
requiring the approval from local cultural relics protection
department.
</P>
<P>
Many local people have given dinosaur eggs they have discovered
to the museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
