<HEADLINE> Japan-Russia Summit set November 1-2 in Eastern Siberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto will hold talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
November 1-2 in Krasnoyarsk, eastern Siberia, the top government
spokesman announced today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was arranged in accordance with an agreement between
Hashimoto and Yeltsin when they met in Denver in June, Chief
Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Yeltsin have agreed on regular reciprocal visits
to improve bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Hashimoto is expected to seek Yeltsin's
understanding on Japan's diplomatic policy toward Russia so as to
pave the way for resolving a long-standing bilateral territorial
dispute over four Russian-held islands off Japan's northernmost
main island of Hokkaidao, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has already set forth three policy principles toward
Russia -- trust, mutual benefit and a long-term perspective -- to
improve bilateral relations which have been marred by the
territorial row.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will also exchange views on bilateral economic
cooperation in such fields as energy development in Siberia and
the Russian Far East, according to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
