<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rate in South Africa Stabilized: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Crime levels have
stabilised in South Africa and in some categories are decreasing,
Sydney Mufamadi, Minister of Safety and Security said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But the country is still facing high levels of violent crime,
the minister was quoted by today's local media as saying.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the third quarterly crime report for 1977, Mufamadi
said none of the 20 most serious crime tendencies had shown an
increase.
</P>
<P>
"It appears that we have halted the deterioration, crime
levels are stabilizing and decreasing," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the police forces would open a new detective
academy in Pretoria next month which would inject fresh blood
into the detective service and enhance police's capacity to clear
cases.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern about large increases in the number of
escapees from detention or lawful custody, and the murder of
police officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the security chief, a total of 3,386 detainees
escaped from police custody between January 1996 and March 1997,
and more than 70 percent of them were detained in connection with
charges of murder, rape and armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
The murder of police officials alos increased by almost 30
percent during the past 12 months, Mufamadi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
