<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Groups Secure Education Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Wang Wanhui, a member of the
Primi ethnic group who spent her childhood in a mountainous area
of southwest China's Yunnan province, is now an animal husbandry
engineer, a much-admired profession in this part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Wang's backward life changed when she entered Yunnan
Agricultural University as one of the small number of young people
in her village to study at college.
</P>
<P>
40 years ago, most of the ethnic minority people had no access
to education.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, getting an education is no longer so strange to the
people of her village. There are 2.2 million minority students in
the province studying at universities or schools, accounting for
35 percent of all the province's students. The province has 10
million people from 25 ethnic minority groups, about one third of
the province's total population.
</P>
<P>
There were only five middle schools, 45 primary schools, and 75
missionary schools in Yunnan 40 years ago, with a total number of
ethnic minority students of just about 20,000. At that time few of
the ethnic minorities could go to primary schools. 10 ethnic
minority groups, including Derung, Va, and Lisu, were still using
beans as calculators and had no written language.
</P>
<P>
Things changed after the founding of the People's Republic of
China in 1949. Because of the central government policies, the
number of people with an education among ethnic minority groups
increased rapidly.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, some 600 million yuan (about 72 million US
dollars) has been spent by the provincial government on building
3,000 primary schools and special middle schools for ethnic
minority students.
</P>
<P>
People of the nation's ethnic minorities have been encouraged
to send their children to school, and 97 percent of the children
of ethnic minorities now attend school.
</P>
<P>
In the fierce college admission competition, ethnic minority
students benefit from the government's preferential policies,
especially those from under-developed areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 million yuan will be added to education funds for
minority areas in Yunnan to help people there complete their
nine-year compulsory education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
