<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Confers With Israeli President Weizman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, on her first Middle East visit since
taking office, stressed the U.S. commitment to Israel in achieving
peace with security.
</P>
<P>
Albright conferred this morning with Israeli President Ezer
Weizman at the presidential residence in Jerusalem after arriving
from Ben-Gurion Airport, where she was welcomed by Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
She told a press conference after the meeting that the U.S. is
with Israel in its battle against terrorism and in the struggle to
apprehend those who orchesrated terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the U.S. supports Israel's insistence on the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to "fulfill its
responsibilities and obligations it has undertaken."
</P>
<P>
"We are with you in the determination that those committed
terror will not succeed, now or ever, in preventing the
possibilities of peace between Israel and the Palestinians, and
throughout the Middle East region from becoming a reality," she
added.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed that during her three-day visit here she
will focus on the security issue in discussions with Israeli and
PNA leaders, adding that both sides should take on "mutual
responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
However, she admitted that real security was inseparable from
the path of real peace.
</P>
<P>
In a large part of her speech, Albright stressed the special
and important relations between the U.S. and Israel, which she
described as "deeply-rooted in history and shared values" in
various areas.
</P>
<P>
She reaffirmed that the U.S. "is absolutely committed to
maintaining Israel's military qualitative edge" in the region.
</P>
<P>
She said that the U.S., joined by Israel and its Arab
partners, would strive to achieve not only peace between Israel
and the Palestinians, but also a comprehensive peace in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Albright added that U.S. President has extended an invitation
to President Weizman, the nominal head of state in Israel, to
visit Washington in early October.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting and the breakfast with Weizman, Albright
is to be accompanied by the president to visit the people wounded
in last Thursday's triple suicide bombing in Jerusalem's Ben
Yehuda pedestrian mall.
</P>
<P>
The terror attack, the second in five weeks, killed eight
people including three suicide bombers and wounded over 190
others.
</P>
<P>
This, together with the previous one on July 30 in which 17
people including two suicide bombers were killed and 170 others
wounded, was claimed by the militant Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Following the wave of attacks, Israel has imposed tough
sanctions against the Palestinians, and conditioned a resumption
of peace talks on the PNA's actions to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The terror attacks have cast dark shadows over Albright's
first trip to the region, which is designed to revive the
deeply-troubled Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the two sides have been frozen since last
March when Israel began building the Har Homa settlement in the
disputed East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Late today, Albright will hold formal talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and opposition Labor party leader Ehud
Barak. On Thursday, she is expected to meet with PNA President
Yasser Arafat and with Netanyahu for the second time in a bid to
narrow the gap between the two sides so to get the peace process
back on track.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, she will hold another meeting with Arafat before
leaving for Syria at the second leg of her Middle East trip, which
will also take her to Egypt, Jordan and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
