<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants Expansion of Pacific Navies' Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today hoped
that efforts would be made to increase the membership of the
"Helicopter Operation Onboard Ships Other Than Aircraft Carriers"
(known as "PAC HOSTAC") forum.
</P>
<P>
PAC HOSTAC could be an important confidence-building forum to
help maintain regional peace and stability, Royal Malaysian Navy
(RMN) Fleet Operations Commander Rear Admiral Mohamed Hussin Tamby
said while opening the three-day Sixth Pacific conference on PAC
HOSTAC here.
</P>
<P>
"I hope efforts would be made to increase the membership of
this forum to further consolidate and enhance the relationships
between navies," he said.
</P>
<P>
PAC HOSTAC presently comprises Australia, Canada, Indonesia,
New Zealand, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand,
the United States and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Hussin said that the RMN placed great emphasis on this
forum as it provides an invaluable mechanism for navy-to-navy
contact especially in the form of helicopter-and-ship
interoperability, ships documentation and cross-deck operations.
</P>
<P>
Such measures are necessary to ensure international helicopter
operations could be conducted safely and effectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 navy personnel from the 10 Asia-Pacific countries are
attending the conference aimed at maintaining coordination,
updating procedures and technical data, and discussing and
exchanging experiences between the navies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
