<HEADLINE> Kenya Acts to Strengthen Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has announced the
separation of the power generation function in the energy sector
from that of distribution and transmission to enhance the
efficiency of the sector, Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Kirugi 'Mukindia said the state-owned
Kenya Power and Lighting Company (KPLC) was divided into two
companies responsible for power distribution and transmission,
and power generation respectively in a bid to enhance the sector.
</P>
<P>
The separation of the two functions in the power sector was
aimed at paving way for entry of private sector players into the
sector, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The separation of functions is in accordance with the reform
timetable of the energy sector agreed upon by the Kenyan
government and the World Bank, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister said legislation to facilitate independent
private sector players in the power generation industry was
underway and the Electric Power bill published recently would be
discussed in Kenyan parliament soon.
</P>
<P>
Late July, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a
three-year loan package to kenya worth 215 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government held a week-long discussions with the
IMF and the World Bank over the suspended loan package and
promised to take actions to meet the conditions set by the two
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The conditions include strengthening of the energy sector,
establishing an independent anti-corruption authority and
ensuring autonomy of the Kenya Revenue Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
