<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Blames Foreign Sabotage in Ties with S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said Tuesday it would
working together with South Africa to check any further
machinations by countries that do not wish Africa well by creating
rift between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The reported strain in the relations between Nigeria and South
Africa was orchestrated by some foreign government, said Alhaji
Idrisu Alhassan Kpaki, minister of state for foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, belonging to similar international
organizations, were working towards improving existing bilateral
relations and promoting the cause of Africans, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Nigeria's move towards Asia for economic cooperation, the
minister said, "Nigeria is not changing its friends but is making
new friends", the official newspaper New Nigerian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks one week before a two-day visit
to Nigeria by South Africa's Vice-President Thambo Mbeki from
September 17 to 18.
</P>
<P>
It is noted increasing diplomatic moves between the two
countries recently indicated a warm-up in bilateral relations
which became frosty since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two leading African countries fell to an
all-time low in late 1995, when South Africa led the campaign in
the Commonwealth that suspended Nigeria's membership for
executing Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Ministry Chief Tom Ikimi visited South Africa
last week to deliver a special message from Head of State Abacha to
President Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Reports say South Africa has agreed not to oppose Nigeria "in
any way" at the October Commonwealth Summit in Edinburgh,
Scotland, which will take the final decision on Nigeria's
membership.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also reportedly agreed to cooperate with the
Economic Community of West African States, in which Nigeria is a
key player, in its effort to restore the legitimate government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in Sierra Leone, who was ousted in a
coup on May 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
