<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Cut One Third of Defense Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is planning to
reduce one third of its defense force over the next five years to save
expenditure for purchase of advanced military hardware, local daily
the citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the disarmament is that 50 percent of the military
budget should been spent on military personnel, making it very difficult
to upgrade and renew military equipment, Defense Department spokesman
Jack Grundlig was quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's current military budget is 9.58 billion Rand (two
billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Grundlig said the reduction of military personnel would enable the
department to set aside about one billion Rand (213 million U.S.
Dollars) a year towards buying new military hardware and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Some western countries, including Britain, Germany and Spain, have
been trying to sell packages of weapons to the South African military,
which complains that the key arms in use are either obsolete or in
poor condition.
</P>
<P>
The weapons offered by western countries include aircraft, warships
and submarines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
