<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neo-Stone Age Relics Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists
recently excavated an ancient site of the famous Yangshao Culture
in north China.
</P>
<P>
The site, located at Diaoyutai, Quyang County, Hebei Province,
yielded a large cache of vessels made of stone, bone and pottery.
</P>
<P>
The site was part of the late Yangshao Culture dating back some
4,000 to 5,000 years. A large number of tombs, houses and cities
have been unearthed in central and north China since the beginning
of the 20th century, with the finds verifying that China was a
mature agricultural society some 6,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Yangshao Culture, together with other Neo-Stone Age
cultures such as the Longshan Culture which lived along the Yellow
River, preceded the establishment of China's first dynasty in the
21st century B.C.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing to Relocate Australian Headquarters to Brisbane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Australia Limited
will move its Australian headquarters from Sydney to Brisbane, a
city in east Australia's Queensland state, Queensland Premier Rob
Borbidge said today.
</P>
<P>
Queensland had been negotiating with the company since May and
the deal was sealed earlier this week, the premier was quoted by
the Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Significantly, having Boeing in Brisbane will mean, that in
terms of aerospace defense industries, we will have the world's
leading corporation making Brisbane home for everything that it
does in Australia," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has been established in Australia for 60 years and
employs 1,700 people. A subsidiary company, AeroSpace
Technologies, is a major exporter of aerospace structures for the
world's leading aircraft manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, 1,027 kilometers away from Brisbane, Boeing
Australia Managing Director David Gray confirmed the premier's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
"We have made no secret over the last few months that we
intended to move," Gray said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Boeing Australia Limited is part of the Boeing Company which
last year booked more than 49 billion US dollars in world sales.
</P>
<P>
Boeing had held discussions with government representatives
from Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland states as well as
Canberra before deciding to relocate, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a competitive business environment compared to the
other states, certainly in terms of lower state taxes and
charges...," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Borbidge declined to disclose some of the sweeteners, or
incentives, his government offered Boeing, saying they were
confidential.
</P>
<P>
Ron Phillips, deputy leader of the opposition in New South
Wales state where Sydney is located, said higher taxes were behind
Boeing's move.
</P>
<P>
Phillips said the move was a direct result of state tax hikes
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Both Borbidge and Gray did not say when the relocation will
begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Opens Three Expressways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Three expressways
simultaneously opened to the traffic today in northeast China's
Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The total mileage for Jilin's freeway system stands at 313
km. The three new expressway, which stretch a total of 179 km,
were built at a cost of 3.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Two of the new expressways originate in Changchun, the
provincial capital, with one running to Jilin city and the other
to Yingchengzi. The third is a ring-road around Changchun.
</P>
<P>
The province is one the nation's major grain producers and an
industrial manufacturing base for motor vehicles and chemical
products.
</P>
<P>
The total lack of expressways prior to 1995 greatly hampered
Jilin's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Changchun-Siping Expressway, the first in the province, was
completed in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local officials report that the province plans to introduce
more overseas funds for infrastructure construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
