<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 80,000 Ugandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 10 (xinhua) -- About 80,000 people died of
malaria in Uganda last year, reported the local daily '' The New
Vision'' today.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for about 22 percent of all deaths in the
country, Crispus Kiyonga, Ugandan Health Minister was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said another major killer disease, AIDS, caused the death
of 38,102 people, bringing the total to 118,060 deaths for the
two diseases in 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 of AIDS victims are below the age of 12, he
said, adding that although malaria weas killing far more people,
AIDS poses a bigger threat.
</P>
<P>
The number of related disease like TB have also gone up in
the country, according to Kiyonga.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 1997-98 financial year, 9 billion Shillings
(about 9 million U.S. Dollars) have been set aside in the
ministry's budget for AIDS control and prevention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
