<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-resident Indians' Investment Allowed in More Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
further liberalized investment norms for non-resident Indians
(NRIs) by allowing them to invest in nearly all infrastructure
sectors in the country, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The investment ceiling has been removed and NRIs are now
allowed to hold up to 100 percent of stake in these ventures. The
investments by NRIs and overseas corporate bodies (OCBs) in
several new sectors including mining, would now move through the
automatic approval window operated by the Reserve Bank of India
(RBI).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the list of industries and items included in the
automatic route for NRIs/OCBs investments was restricted to 35
high priority industries.
</P>
<P>
The list has now been expanded by 25 industries and items to
60. This includes mining of iron ore and metal ore (excluding
uranium), manufacture of food products, cotton textiles, wool,
silk, man-made fibers, textile products, basic chemicals and
chemical products.
</P>
<P>
The investment limit of 74 percent has been removed and NRIs
are now allowed to invest up to 100 percent in oil and gas field
services, except exploration and production services.
</P>
<P>
The changes are in consonance with the government's strategy to
progressively liberalize procedures governing foreign investment
and foreign technology transfer, the same sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0202 </DOCNO>
