<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Operation Normal in Philippines: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the Philippine
Central Bank said today that operations of the country's banks
have remained normal despite rumors of an impending bank run.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson said his statement was based on the findings of
the agents of the National Bureau of Investigation (NBI) who
reported to the central bank that no bank run is taking place
right now.
</P>
<P>
Singson admitted that there was a time when one of the banks
sought the financial help of the central bank because of an
unusual volume of withdrawals by its depositors.
</P>
<P>
But the governor said he did not consider this as some kind of
a panic withdrawal as far as the central bank is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Singson did not disclose the name of the bank which borrowed
money from the central bank in order to beef up its financial
resources in the midst of the peso depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Singson was alarmed over the rumors that the country's
banks were experiencing troubles as a result of the peso
depreciation that started haunting the banking industry since July
11.
</P>
<P>
This prompted the central bank to seek the help of the NBI to
find the veracity of these rumors and take action against those
who are spreading the rumors which may have caused panic
withdrawals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
