<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT,  September 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- United States Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, on her first Middle East visit since taking office,
stressed the U.S. commitment to Israel in achieving peace with
security.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a press conference Wednesday after the meeting
with Israeli President Ezer Weizman that the U.S. is with Israel
in its battle against terrorism and in the struggle to apprehend
those who orchesrated terrorist attacks. (Israel-Albright Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SHENYANG, CHINA -- China's first large photo album illustrating
Deng Xiaoping's theory and practice of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics has been recently published by the
Liaoning Ethnic Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
The "Cross-century Historical Picture Album", with more than
600 pictures and 130,000 Chinese characters, which describes the
forming and the main content of Deng's theory on building
socialism with Chinese characteristics, also shows the great
achievements China has scored in the reform, opening up and
socialist modernization drive over the past two decades and
reflects the country's bright future. (China-Picture Album-Deng
Xiaoping)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The dispute over who should represent the ruling
party in the presidential election in Yugoslavia's republic of
Montenegro has developed into a veto game between federal and
regional authorities.
</P>
<P>
The election is scheduled for October 5, but the leadership of
the republic's ruling Socialist Democratic Party has been deeply
divided over who should be nominated to represent the party in the
election. One faction nominated the incumbent President Momir
Bulatovic, while the other preferred the current Prime Minister
Milo Djukanovic. (Yugoslavia-President-Candidate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said here Tuesday
that the upcoming visit to the United States by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin will provide an important opportunity for constructive
work.
</P>
<P>
"President Jiang's visit is an important opportunity, not so
much for grand statements and dramatic gestures, as for
constructive work on common challenges," he told students and
faculty members at American University.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton specified such issues like easing tension on
the Korean Peninsula, stopping the spread of nuclear weapons,
protecting the environment and ending trade barriers, for the two
countries to work together. (US-China-Visit)
</P>
