<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Cotton Production Below Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 10 (Xinhua) --About 278,000 tons of cotton
were produced this year by Zimbabwe's cotton growers, which are below
the forecast production of between 285,000 and 300,000 tons, the
daily The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Cotton Managing Director Sylvester Nguni said Tuesday the
production of cotton was affected by excessive rains which caused
waterlogging and leaching.
</P>
<P>
Peasants and small-scale commercial cotton growers shared
around one billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 87 million US Dollars)
from the 190,000 tons of raw cotton they sold to the cotton
company so far this season.
</P>
<P>
Cotton has been a profitable cash crop for Zimbabwe's rural
communities. Over 800 million Zimbabwe Dollars (approximate 70
US Dollars) had gone to peasant farmers in the communal lands.
</P>
<P>
The cotton company, set for privatisation next month, buys
cotton through 16 depots in the major cotton growing areas and
the overhelming bulk of its suppliers are peasant and small-scale
growers producing high-quality hand-picked cotton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
