<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life's Not Bad For Teachers in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- More Shanghai citizens
believe that despite the low pay and occasional lack of respect,
being a teacher isn't such a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Jiaxiang, deputy president of Shanghai Normal College,
said that 7,000 applicants had competed for some 1,200 positions
available at the school this semester.
</P>
<P>
"That is, only one out of every six could be enrolled. But several
years ago, the ratio was one out of every two or three," he told
Xinhua prior to Teachers' Day, which falls on September 10.
</P>
<P>
In early June, He recalled, as more as 40 thousand prospective
students once rushed to the college's conference hall for
information on enrollment procedures. The hall can hold only
several thousand people.
</P>
<P>
Many high school headmasters came to his office to make
teaching offers to graduates, Xiang said. At present, an opening
for a high school teacher in Shanghai draws as more as 30 applicants.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is China's biggest commercial and trade center. Nearly
160,000 teachers work in the city.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, teachers colleges in Shanghai, and throughout
China as well, have suffered from two major problems: few
high school students registered to take entrance examinations to
study at teachers colleges, and many graduates from teachers
colleges were reluctant to work in high schools.
</P>
<P>
Low pay is one of the main reasons.
</P>
<P>
But things now have been somewhat changed. Salaries for
teachers in the municipality have doubled from 1992 and are 10
percent higher than those for government servants. according to
figures provided by the Shanghai Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the money spent by the government on building
housing for teachers increased by 465.7 percent in the 1991-95
period over the 1986-90 period.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody can witness the improvement in teachers' conditions,
thanks to the overall development of the national economy" said Li
Mingyang, an official from the Shanghai Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
China has a time-honored tradition of respecting teachers and
intellectuals. But in the chaotic Culture Revolution (1966-76),
educators were reviled and some even tortured.
</P>
<P>
After the reform and opening up policy was introduced in the
late 1970s, they again received their due respect.
</P>
<P>
The central government has convened meetings every year calling
on local officials to deal seriously with teachers' low pay. Some
regulations hint that if officials continue to ignore the
situation, they will have difficulties being promoted.
</P>
<P>
These methods have proved effective. Official figures show
that between 1985 and 1990, 25 percent of Shanghai's college
teachers had opted for more lucrative jobs. But the rate had been
brought down to four percent by 1995.
</P>
<P>
In primary and high schools, where the work was usually more
difficult, 3,200 teachers quit their jobs in 1993. However, the
number dropped to 1,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many people think that time is still needed before teachers can
improve their overall social status. But there is no doubt the
profession will become increasingly attractive.
</P>
<P>
"At least the income is stable," Li Mingyang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Per Capita Debt Burden Stands at 133 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The present per capita debt
burden of Bangladesh is about 133 U.S. dollars, according to a
local news report today.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh may land up in debt-trap within the next 10 years
unless steps are taken to stem the rising trend of debt burden,
the report quoted a senior official from the Ministry of planning
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The total national debt, as a percentage of the GDP is 54
percent and debt service liability is 18 percent as percentage of
exports," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He added that with about 50 percent of the population living
below the poverty line and a population growth rate of about 2
percent, management of this South Asian country is extremely
difficult.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh with a population of over 120 million and over 800
persons per square kilometer, is one of the most densely populated
country in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the population of Bangladesh will be
doubled within the next 35 years if the present rate of population
growth continues.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that poverty, as a situation of
deprivation of the basic needs, affects the majority of the
population, 80 percent of whom, still live in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of the population are landless and about 10
million people are completely assetless and rootless, he noted,
adding that about 50 percent of mothers in the rural areas get
less than 1,200 calories a day against the minimum requirement of
about 2,300 calories, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the percentage of underweight children under five
years in this debt-burdened country is 66, the official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
