<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Witnesses Booming Private Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in the
north China city of Tianjin has evolved into a driving force for
local economic development and contributed 3.1 percent to the
city's tax revenues during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The city's nearly 240,000 private businesses employed over
500,000 people by the end of June. Some 190,000 of the firms are
engaged in the service sector, with the remainder in wide-ranging
fields such as manufacturing and construction.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has introduced various preferential policies to
encourage growth in the sector. For example, the Wuqing County
Industrial Park has already attracted three private enterprises,
with preparations for the entry of an additional 12 ventures.
</P>
<P>
The city is home to 15 private enterprise groups, and 195
businesses involving investments of over five million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Private firms have offered lucrative salaries to attract
scientists, retired officials, and senior intellectuals. Related
individuals currently account for nearly 30 percent of total
employment in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The private sector also serves as a reemployment channel by
providing jobs for over 47,000 workers declared redundant by state
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
