<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planning Film Launched in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A documentary film on
family planning services in Tanzania has been launched in this east
African country.
</P>
<P>
The film, based on a research on familiy planning from October
to November, 1995, will be shown on the four TV stations who will
play a major role in enlightening the people on family planning
matters, said Deborah Mwenda, Chairperson of the Tanzania Media
Women Association (TAMWA) while launching the film on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two pamphlets on the research will be also available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
Deborah said that although family planning activities started in
the country in 1959, so far less than 10 percent of the people are
practising it because of "myths surrounding family planning" and
"family planning and Islam".
</P>
<P>
She urged, "Much more work, therefore, needs to be done by
non-governrmental organizations including TAMWA to raise people's
awareness of family planning.
</P>
<P>
The film was sponsored by Pathfinder International whose
president Dan Pellegrum said at the launching of the film that
family planning is very important in creating a better society.
</P>
<P>
Between 2,000 and 4,000 women die every year in Tanzania due to
complications from pregnancy and during child birth, the figures
translate that more than 10 women die every day because of pregnant
related problems and during delivery, according to TAMWA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
