<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Freezes Textile Tariff Cut During 2000-2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard announced in Sydney today the federal government's
decision to impose a five-year freeze from 2000 on slashing
tariffs on the textile, clothing and footwear (TCF).
</P>
<P>
Howard said the five-year freeze would enable Australian TCF
firms to strengthen their competitive positions after a period of
significant change, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation
reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision was apparently made by the government under the
pressure from local TCF industries. The industries, which employ
96,000 workers, have been lobbying intensively against the
proposals on TCF tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
The planned reductions of TCF tariffs would continue through to
the year 2000 and would then be maintained at the same level from
July 1, 2000 until January 1, 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on clothing and finished textiles would move from
current levels of 34 percent before being frozen at 25 percent on
July 1, 2000 until January 1, 2005, when they would move to 17.5
percent, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Footwear, carpets and cotton fabric tariffs would be frozen at
15 percent in 2000 before moving to 10 percent in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The decision is almost identical to that adopted by the
government earlier this year for the car manufacturing industry,
with the government responding to wide-spread community concern
about the loss of blue-collar jobs in traditional manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from four domestic car makers, the Howard
government on July 5 accepted a four-year freeze on car tariffs
from 2000 to 2004.
</P>
<P>
With a jobless rate of 8.7, unemployment has been one of the
several issues high on the agenda of the Howard government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Textile Mills May Be transferred to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government is
considering a proposal to transfer the ownership of some
state-owned textile mills to workers and employees as part of its
privatization program, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ownership will be transferred according to the existing
Company Law, the newspaper the Independent said, adding that the
Bangladesh prime minister has directed the authorities concerned
to explore avenues for handling over the ownership of the
state-owned enterprises (SOE) to workers and employees.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations have been made in this regard by a committee
set up on June 9,1997 to determine the terms and conditions for
handling over the ownership of public sector textile mills, the
newspaper stated.
</P>
<P>
According to the recommendations, the workers and employees will
have to clear the long-term loans of the state-owned textile
mills, if they take over their ownership while the government will
transfer its shares to them free of cost, the Independent said.
</P>
<P>
The workers and employees will buy these mills in open tender,
the paper reported, adding that these mills will not be allowed to
change over to any other business and could be permitted to run as
textile mills only.
</P>
<P>
Beside, the government will establish some regulatory
authorities to ensure the smooth running of these mills and
provide some extra facilities to these enterprises, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
As facilities, interests on outstanding loans at the time of
transfer will be written-off, the paper stated.
</P>
<P>
There will be exemption from taxes on the import of spare parts
and machinery, the paper said. Besides, banks will be also
encouraged to provide soft loans at low and simple interest.
</P>
<P>
According to the recommendations, a mill can be transferred to
its workers and employees if a majority or 65 percent of them
express a desire to own the mill and run it as a public limited
company, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
This action taken by the government aims at alleviating the
government's financial burden caused by the SOE sector. The public
sector corporations have been sustaining a lost of around 25
billion taka (about 568 million U.S. dollars) a year causing a
huge drain on the national exchequer, the newspaper added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
