<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Treasurer Hints at Rate Cut for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Treasurer
Winston Peters said today that he planned to lower the current
business tax rates next year, a local press report said.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement in response to questions at an economic
meeting in Masterton, 100 km northeast of Wellington,
</P>
<P>
He said he planned to bring the corporate rate into line with
the personal tax rates, raising the possibility of two rates for
businesses.
</P>
<P>
At present, companies pay a flat rate of 33 cents for each
dollar on profit while individuals are taxed at 21.5 percent on
incomes up to 34,000 NZ dollars and 33 percent on incomes over
that amount.
</P>
<P>
"The work is going into it now. Hopefully we will complete it
as soon as possible. We will be announcing it in the Budget next
year, or sooner," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's good for business, it's good for the country, it's good
for production, it's good for growth," he stated.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for Peters' office later downplayed the
significance of Peters' statement, saying all tax rates were being
 examined to help lower business running costs.
</P>
<P>
"The Government would be in a position to make decisions about
that around Budget time next year," the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
