<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Currency Falls 18-month Low Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali currency of
rupee depreciated for the third time in two weeks and hit an
18-month low, forcing the central bank to intervene again.
</P>
<P>
To meet the pressing market demand, the Nepal Rastra Bank (NRB)
on Monday evening sold 16.5 million U.S. dollars to commercial
banks at the rate of 58.70 rupee at the request of the Foreign
Exchange Dealers Association.
</P>
<P>
But on Tuesday and Wednesday, the NRB has refixed the buying
and selling rates of the greenback at rupee 58.50 and rupee 59.05
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The NRB intervened first on August 27 when the Nepali rupee
fell by 50 paisa and was sold at 58.05 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
From September 4, the Nepali currency fell down further to
58.30 per dollar, and the buying rate of the dollar was reset at
57.75 rupee from 57.50 rupee.
</P>
<P>
Since the Indian rupee keeps falling against the dollar
recently and hit a 19-month low of 36.70 Tuesday, the Nepali
currency, pegged to the Indian currency at a fixed rate of 1:1.6,
has no other way but to follow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
