<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.A.F.'s Woman Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Sheila Widnall, the first
woman secretary of the United States Air Force, said today she
would step down from her four-year tenure on October 31.
</P>
<P>
Widnall, who was named Air Force secretary in 1993, formally
announced her intention in a letter to President Bill Clinton and
Secretary of Defense William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Widnall said she would go back to the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, where she had been associate provost and a faculty
member for more than 28 years before being named Air Force
secretary. She is an expert on aeronautics and astronautics.
</P>
<P>
Widnall's resignation came just weeks after the Air Force's
Chief of Staff, General Ronald Fogleman, quit his post over a
controversy about a terrorist attack on U.S. troops in Saudi
Arabia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Fogleman quit in July, saying he felt the air commander at the
scene was being unfairly blamed after the terrorist bombing on a
U.S. military housing complex in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, killed 19
Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
