<HEADLINE> Half-Year Tourist Arrivals Edge Up in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Thailand
in the first half of this year grew by only 1.8 percent over the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The number is much lower than expected by the Tourism Authority
of Thailand (TAT), which had targeted a 7.4-percent growth to a
total of 7.84 million arrivals for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
In fact there may be only a 4-percent growth by the end of the
year, The Bangkok Post today quoted TAT Deputy Governor Juthamas
Siriwan as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months, arrivals from ASEAN countries,
which supply more than half of all Thailand's tourists, dropped
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Economic problems and depreciation of currencies in the region
are deterring people from making overseas trips.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is promoting an "Amazing Thailand" campaign for 1998
and 1999 to attract 17 million foreigners in the two years.
</P>
<P>
Last week TAT Governor Seree Wangpaichitr admitted that it
would be difficult to attain the target, but he said the country
can still meet the revenue target of 600 billion baht (about 16
billion U.S. dollars) set for the two-year campaign.
</P>
<P>
Juthamas said the TAT will set sight on the 2 million transit
passengers per year and allure them to do shopping at airports or
nearby areas. Besides, she plans to form some promotion groups to
do direct marketing on roadshows to major markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
