<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Ethnic Group Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore today met with 12 people
of various ethnic groups, including Polish, Hungarian and Irish,
who were worried they would be left out of a racial reconciliation
effort now focused more on skin color.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced his year-long drive to improve race relations
in June.
</P>
<P>
"Ethnic Americans in particular were very supportive of what
the president was doing, but were concerned that the initiative
was being put in black-versus-white-versus-Latino perspectives,"
said Brian O'Dwyer, who represented the New York-based Irish
American Immigration Coalition.
</P>
<P>
He said the president and vice president were "extraordinarily
sympathetic to our viewpoint" after each group presented its
concerns.
</P>
<P>
A major dilemma for Clinton's initiative has been determining
how much attention to give black-white relations without giving
short shrift to other races and ethnic groups. At its first
meeting in July, the president's seven-member race advisory board
split over this issue.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the meeting was part of
an continuing outreach effort to prevent the feelings of exclusion
voiced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Rotondaro, executive director of the National Italian
American Foundation, said several ethnic organizations planned to
gather here Wednesday to plan ways to work with Clinton's
initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
