<HEADLINE> U.S. Suspends Deportation of Six Irish Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today it suspended deportation proceedings for six Irish nationals
who have completed their prison sentences for various crimes
involving the Irish Republican Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
The move was described as a gesture to encourage the peace
process in Northern Ireland as the Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican
Army's political wing, formally signed a declaration renouncing
violence earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno said she acted on a formal request
from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and suspended the
deportation of the six individuals "who have engaged in activity
on behalf" of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
The six Irish people, who had completed their prison sentences,
had been convicted of various crimes involving the IRA. They were
facing deportation for making untrue statements to immigration
officials.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Reno, Albright said the measure was taken to
advance the ongoing peace process and the talks in Northern
Ireland. 
</P>
