<HEADLINE> Major Thai Banks Raise Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Leading Thai commercial banks
 raised their lending rates by a significant margin Tuesday as the
country's economy remained under the pressure of tight liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank, Siam Commercial Bank (SCB) and Bank of Ayudhya
also boosted their lending rates by half a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank's minimum lending rate (MLR) now stands at 14.25
percent while its minimum overdraft rate (MOR) is at 14.75 percent
and its minimum retail rate (MRR) 14.5 percent, according to The
Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
At SCB and Bank of Ayudhya, the increase leaves their MLR at
14.25 percent and their MOR and MRR at 14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai Military Bank also raised its rates. Now its MLR stands at
13.50 percent and its MOR and MRR, 14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the state-owned Krung Thai Bank did not adjust its
rates this time, in line with government policy.
</P>
<P>
Some bank executives said the hike is in accordance with higher
costs and the changed situation in the money market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
