<HEADLINE> Beijing Marks Teachers Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal
government hosted a conference on Tuesday to mark China's Teachers
Day, which will be celebrated today.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhijian, deputy secretary of the Beijing municipal committee
of the Chinese Communist Party, expressed support and
congratulations for teachers working in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Li said that teachers working in the capital must work hard to
contribute to the city's education program.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the city has invested 800 million yuan (100
million US dollars) over the past two years to either construct or
renovate schools and housing for teachers.
</P>
<P>
Despite China's time-honored tradition of respecting teachers,
the income level for teachers was amongst the lowest in the nation
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders have launched intensive campaigns over the past
few years to improve the conditions of teachers and improve the
quality of education as a means of fulfilling the nation's
modernization dream.
</P>
<P>
Officials presented awards to more than 1,000 outstanding
teachers attending yesterday's conference. 
