<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Threatens Peru Historical Treasure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A huge forest fire Tuesday came
as close as 200 meters to Peru's Inca citadel of Machu Picchu, a
UNESCO-proclaimed World Heritage Site.
</P>
<P>
Peru's civil defense chief, Hector Nurena, said it was very
difficult to control the fire, which had destroyed 1,500 acres of
vegetation, because dense smoke and heat hampered hundreds of
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
The smoke caused poor visibility and worry about asphyxiation,
Nurena said. Four helicopters carrying water from nearby rivers
also had no option but wait on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"But there has been no damage to the citadel," Nurena noted.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters, policemen, soldiers and volunteers cut down trees
around the citadel and poured water on the earth to prevent flames
licking the ancient center.
</P>
<P>
Now the major threat comes from winds which have carried embers
across the forest to spark fresh fires all over the area which is
about 1,150 kilometers southeast of Lima.
</P>
<P>
The area was sealed off to visitors and will not be reopened
for at least a week. Hundreds of people who stayed in nearby
hotels and villages were evacuated by civil defense workers.
</P>
<P>
Machu Picchu, one of Latin America's most famous tourist
attractions, was discovered by a United States archeologist, Hiram
Bingham, in 1912. Archeologists believe the ruins were a key
religious center of the pre-Columbian Inca empire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Imposes National Ban on Land Clearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has imposed a national cessation to land clearance activities in a
bid to curb forest fires which have caused smoke and haze
problems, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The president has ordered plantations, timber companies and
settler farmers to stop all land clearing activities," Environment
Minister Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said here last night after meeting
with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Smoke and haze caused by fires have affected millions of lives
in Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that about 1,053 fires have razed approximately
300,000 hectares of forest in South Sumatra, Jambi, Riau and West
Kalimantan, causing health problems, flights cancellations and air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of fires have produced a thick pall of smoke over many
parts of Indonesia and neighboring Malaysia and Singapore. At
least three airports in Indonesia have been shut down since the
weekend because of low visibility and cars have been forced to
drive with lights on during daytime in some areas.
</P>
<P>
The smoke has worsened already chronic air pollution over
Jakarta, and a thick haze has enveloped Malaysia's capital, Kuala
Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sarwono estimated that as many as 20 million people
could suffer respiratory, eye and other health problems because of
the smoke.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia and Singapore have provided information from
satellites to help track the progress of fires. Malaysia also has
started a cloud-seeding program to trigger rainfall to clear the
air.
</P>
<P>
Sarwono said Indonesia would begin a similar artificial rain
project immediately. Officials have said the fires will continue
to burn until extinguished by seasonal monsoon rain.
</P>
<P>
However, meteorologists predict that the rain might be delayed
by months this year because of the El Nino weather phenomenon over
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
El Nino occurs every three to five years and produces climate
abnormalities around the world, including droughts in Indonesia,
other parts of Asia and Australia. The dry spell so far has
devastated harvests of rice, coffee and other crops in Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
