<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devotion, Chinese Teachers' Life Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Chen De, a troubled kid from the
streets, was well on his way to spoiling himself, but someone stood
in his way.
</P>
<P>
His teacher.
</P>
<P>
Within just a year, Chen has become one of the best pupils in his
primary school class. He gives all the credit for his
transformation to Wu Penghua, whom he calls "Teacher Mother."
</P>
<P>
The 51-year-old Wu, who teaches primary school in a remote area
of east China's Anhui Province, thinks of her job as a reflection of
her life values rather than just a way of making a living.
</P>
<P>
She has taught there for 30 years, abandoning her chances of
living in Taiwan or the United States and being transferred to a
job in the city.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer to dedicate all I have to foster talent for our
country," she said.
</P>
<P>
China has more than ten million teachers, most of whom view the
teaching profession as their life's work. In 1988, the Chinese
Government set September 10 as national Teacher's Day.
</P>
<P>
Lu Binglun, who teaches in the Dabie mountainous area in East
China, is one of the many dedicated teachers. At one point in his
life as a businessman, he could earn more money in a couple of
weeks than he can now as a teacher for several months. But he
refuses to quit teaching.
</P>
<P>
"My biggest aspiration is to give these country kids brighter
futures through my work," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
One of Lu's student, Yu Yimei, is now a teacher herself. She
said with appreciation, "Without Teacher Lu's help, I would have
been illiterate."
</P>
<P>
Yu's family was poor, and as a primary school pupil she was
forced to drop out of school. Lu made five visits to Yu's home to
persuade her parents to send her back to the school and he paid
Yu's tuition for several years running.
</P>
<P>
Though living in poverty himself, Lu has helped more than 100
pupils from poor families finish their studies. Many of his
students came back to their hometown after graduation from senior
secondary schools and became wealthy.
</P>
<P>
"The development of education is the basis of modernization of
our country. Students of today are masters of the next century,"
Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
Another teacher in the region, Hu Yonghua, has been teaching in
a middle school for 33 years. "We see the value of our life from
our students," said Hu, who volunteered to give up the chance to
work in Shanghai and teach in the poor mountainous area upon
graduation from university.
</P>
<P>
Despite a lame leg, Hu has spent nearly all his holidays
tutoring his students for free. Thanks to his efforts, the school
became renowned in the province and even in the country. More than
450 university graduates are his students and many of them made
remarkable achievements.
</P>
<P>
"The contribution of teachers to society is being increasingly
admired by more and more people," said Chen Xianzhong, director of
Anhui Provincial Educational Commission.
</P>
<P>
China has a long tradition of respecting teachers, but the
tradition was forsaken during the 10-year Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976), when teachers were reviled and sometimes tortured.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has taken considerable efforts to
improve teachers' living conditions since late 1970s, Chen said,
"We have a lot to do to raise their social and economic
status. And the spirit of utter devotion to teaching and
respecting teachers is yet to be further fostered," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Foreign Minister Says Army United Behind Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Algerian Foreign Minister
Ahmed Attaf said here today the Algerian army stood united behind
the government, adding terrorism in Algeria was doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
Attaf said the Algerian army is "serving the state and its
institutions." He also dismissed the possibility of a military
coup.
</P>
<P>
"We have heard about the army being divided between those who
plead reconciliation and those who plead eradication. Those are,
believe me, speculations," Attaf, on a two-day visit to Finland,
told a news conference held after meeting his Finnish counterpart
Tarja Halonen.
</P>
<P>
Attaf added that terrorism had no future in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Muslim fundamentalists have been battling the authorities since
early 1992 when the government cancelled a general election in
which radical Islamists were on the verge of a victory.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 people have been killed in Algeria's violence.
</P>
<P>
Attaf also denied that the United Nations had offered to
mediate in the conflict and said his country would reject the
world body's intention, if any, to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Attaf is on his first visit to Finland. He visited the
Netherlands early this week and also Denmark early this year. All
of the three European countries are members of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The EU, set to build a free trade bloc with the Mediterranean
countries, is keen to develop relations with Algeria, an African
country in the Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
