<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maldives Bans "Hate Book" on National Heroes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Maldivian government has
banned a local history book on the grounds that it defames past
national heroes.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Ministry of Information, Arts and Culture
said the 284-page book was banned under a Maldivian law that
prohibits the publication of libelous material.
</P>
<P>
The recently published book was written in the Maldivian
language, Dhivehi, by 83-year-old Abdul Hakeem Hussain Maniku.
</P>
<P>
The book, entitled "Lyye" (Yesterday), had created a storm
which initially led to the withdrawal of all copies put on sale as
many claimed that the book was not based on scholarship but on
malicious intent.
</P>
<P>
It has been described by elderly Maldivians as a "hate book."
</P>
<P>
The statement said continued public outcry about its contents
eventually prompted the government to ban the book which contains
slanderous material as well as false allegations and derogatory
language defaming past national heroes.
</P>
<P>
The book spoke about, among others, Sultan Hassan Izzuddin or
Dhon Bandarain, a national hero whose prestige had remained
untarnished for centuries.
</P>
<P>
He liberated the country from the rule of Malabaris in the 18th
century.
</P>
<P>
Others covered in the book include the first president of the
Republic of Maldives, the late Mohamed Amin Didi, and the late
former Prime Minister Abdul Majeed Didi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Chinese President's Visit Important Opportunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here today that the upcoming visit to the United States by
Chinese President Jiang Zemin will provide an important
opportunity for constructive work.
</P>
<P>
"President Jiang's visit is an important opportunity, not so
much for grand statements and dramatic gestures, as for
constructive work on common challenges," he told students and
faculty members at American University.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton specified such issues like easing tension on
the Korean Peninsula, stopping the spread of nuclear weapons,
protecting the environment and ending trade barriers, for the two
countries to work together.
</P>
<P>
"We want a China that works with us to build a secure and
prosperous future," he stressed, adding "America has a profound
interest in seeing that China is stable, open, at peace with its
neighbors."
</P>
<P>
The visit, scheduled for late October, will also offer a chance
"for us to address candidly and face to face our differences on
issues like human rights and religious freedom," President Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
"Sitting down together across the table is far more likely to
produce progress than pointing fingers across the Pacific," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"China is home to a quarter of the world's people. In less than
two decades, its economy may be the largest on earth," President
Clinton said, believing that if the peoples of the United States
and China can find a way to forge the future together, they both
will be better off. 
</P>
