<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Encourages Bold Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia is encouraging foreign
enterprises to invest more boldly in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russian First Vice-Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov made the point
Tuesday while meeting with Belgium Minister of Foreign Affairs
Eric Derycke.
</P>
<P>
During their discussion on bilateral economic and trade
relations, Nemtsov assured Derycke that Russian laws can safeguard
the security of foreign investments. So foreign enterprises had no
need to worry about their investments in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov disclosed that Russia will take further steps to draw
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is now among the countries having the most investments
in eastern Europe. Earlier, in meeting with Gennady Seleznev, the
chairman of Russia's State Duma, Derycke said that Belgium is
optimistic about the future of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Derycke, who arrived in Moscow Monday, also exchanged views
with his Russian counterpart, Yevgeny Primakov, today about
relations between Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), and the situation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Primakov reiterated Russia's opposition to NATO's enlargement,
especially the admission of former Soviet republics. But this did
not mean Russia was also against the European Union having new
members, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
