<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Rate Estimated at 8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate
throughout the 1997/98 fiscal year is expected not to exceed 8
percent, despite the present currency turmoil, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) Sugito said
here today that the ongoing currency problem, which began with the
depreciation of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, will affect
the consumer index price. But it will not be the biggest
contributor to the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the rate for the current fiscal year
will be higher than that in the 1996/97 period.
</P>
<P>
He said the long drought, which started three months ago, will
push up the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
On the tight money policy that followed the problem of the
weakening rupiah, he said it has led to an increase in interest
rates for time deposits.
</P>
<P>
But he said it is unlikely that the ongoing monetary problems
will contribute too much to the inflation rate in the current
fiscal year, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
