<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Capital Turned Into Modern Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Those who have never visited
Lhasa might think that the capital city of the Tibet Autonomous
Region is home to nothing but temples, religious pilgrims and
narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
But upon arrival in the city, visitors may well be taken aback
by the magnificence of the Potala Palace, as well as numerous
modern buildings, 30 m-wide streets and a TV-broadcasting tower.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, Lhasa was a small town of three
sq km in 1951, when the autonomous region was liberated
peacefully. Now, it has been built into a modern city covering 51
sq km with many modern factories, banks, hotels, shops and
apartment complexes.
</P>
<P>
Of Lhasa's 200,000 population, over 20,000 people are engaged
in private business, and several thousands of shops have opened in
the city.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the central government and other parts of the
country, Lhasa has erected modern facilities such as the Lhasa
Holiday Inn Hotel, the Tibet Guesthouse, the Foreign Trade
Building, the Tibet Stadium, and the Post and Telecom Building.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, over 28,400 sq m of residential buildings have
been built or renovated, which has increased the per-capita
housing space to over nine sq m. The running water supply now
covers 70 percent of local residents.
</P>
<P>
"Lhasa is changing too fast," said a retired Tibetan man. "Now
I cannot find many of the old places from my past."
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor Losang Jamcan, Lhasa plans to expand its
urban infrastructures even further.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city will complete a number of projects,
including low-cost apartments, the Lhasa section of the highway to
link Tibet with Sichuan Province, a large trade building, and the
renovation of a local park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
