<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Shoulders Military Modernization Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Polish government today
passed a military modernization plan for the next 15 years that
calls for a leaner and better equipped, trained and commanded
armed force.
</P>
<P>
The move was designed to prepare the country for its admission
into the military alliance, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO), in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Poland will cut the number of troops by 180,000
by the year 2004. The armed forces' infrastructure will also be
pruned by 35 percent and by the end of the century, the term of
compulsory service will be reduced to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The plan also calls for increased military spending on advanced
weaponry and strengthened military training.
</P>
<P>
Poland will have to add 1.5 to 2 billion U.S. dollars to its
military expenditure for its membership in NATO, Defense Minister
Stanislaw Dobrzanski said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
