<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Ports Become Regional Shipping Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- After years of intensified
construction, a large group of ports have been built up in Xiamen,
Zhangzhou and Quanzhou cities in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The ports have emerged as a regional shipping center between
harbors in the Yangtze River Delta and the Zhujiang River Delta,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The coastline along the three cities extends 1,335 km,
including an over 100 km-long section where deepwater ports could
be built.
</P>
<P>
In ancient times, local ports played an important role in
promoting trade and economic relations with foreign countries.
The Quanzhou Port was the starting point of the Silk Road, while
Xiamen Port was one of five largest ports in old China.
</P>
<P>
Since China launched its reform and opening drive in the late
1970s, many new ports have been constructed.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the ports have a combined 151 berths, which handled
24.87 million tons of goods and 414,000 TEUs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The ports have opened dozens of domestic and international
shipping routes including those connecting with Japan, Singapore,
the United States and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The three cities continue to make port building a key economic
task in the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
