<HEADLINE> South China Province to Build World's Largest Computer Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province is making every possible effort to build its Pearl River
Delta into one of the world's largest electronics and computer
production bases in the next five to ten years.
</P>
<P>
A team of businessmen from Guangdong, who were attending the
ongoing '97 China Investment and Trade Talks which opened Monday
in Xiamen, east China's Fujian, gave details of Guangdong's future
economic development plans.
</P>
<P>
They said that during the 1996-2000 period, a total of 48.5
billion US dollars in overseas investment is expected to be used,
19.3 percent more than that in the Eighth Five-Year Plan Period
(1991-1995), and priority will be given to a group of hi-tech
projects.
</P>
<P>
As early as in 1993, Guangdong shifted its economic focus to
hi-tech industry development, including electronic information,
bio-engineering, new materials development, mechanical and
electronical integration and energy, and now the Pearl River Delta
has become a production base of electronic products and computers,
</P>
<P>
Last year, the output value of 1,850 hi-tech products reached
95 billion yuan, amounting for 8.6 percent of the region's gross
value of industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong now has six state-level hi-tech development regions,
including Shenzhen, Guangzhou, Zhongshan, Zhuhai, Foshan and
Huizhou, which have been among the country's top 18, said the
business delegation.
</P>
<P>
And of the country's first group of key hi-tech programs and
leading enterprises, about 20 percent are from Guangdong, the
State Scientific Commission has announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
