<HEADLINE> Uruguayan President Stresses Energy Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan President Julio
Maria Sanguinetti says there is a trend toward an "energy common
market" in Southern America -- besides the political, commercial
and cultural integration.
</P>
<P>
Sanguinetti was speaking today at the opening of an
international meeting on "Integration and Investment on Natural
Gas and Electric Energy in Southern America".
</P>
<P>
He said there have been great changes in the gas and power
industry in the region and there were many opportunities for
businessmen to invest there.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, the demand for electric power had
increased by an average of 5 percent a year. The region needed
a large amount of private capital to meet the demand, the
Uruguayan president stressed.
</P>
<P>
The forum, to finish Wednesday, was organized by the United
States departments of energy and commerce and the U.S. Trading
Development Agency.
</P>
<P>
Energy ministers from Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile,
Paraguay, Uruguay and the United States attended the meeting, as
well as representatives from more than 200 Uruguayan and foreign
companies. 
