<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT September 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The productivity of American workers grew at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 2.7 percent in the second
quarter, the fastest rate in three and an half years, U.S. Labor
Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The gain was much faster than the initially estimated 0.6
percent reported last month and nearly double the 1.4 percent rate
of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- The opposition National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has pledged to continue observing
the Lusaka peace agreement to bring final peace to Angola, a UN
envoy said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Returning from Andulo, a central Angolan city, where he met
UNITA leaders, the United Nations special envoy based in Angola
Blondin Beye told reporters that he formally presented the UN
Security Council Resolution No. 1127 on economic sanctions against
UNITA to its leadership.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The next 25 years will witness an unprecedented
boost in the prominence of developing countries in the world
economy, and five of those nations are likely to change the world
economic map, the World Bank predicted.
</P>
<P>
In its 114-page report "Global Economic Prospects and the
Developing Countries 1997" released here today, the World Bank
said policy reforms and a broadly favorable international economic
environment could allow developing countries to grow between 5 to
6 percent between now and 2020, raising their share of world
output from around one-sixth to nearly one third over the period.
</P>
<P>
The growing importance of developing economies will be
reflected in, and driven by, the emergence of the "Big Five" --
China, India, Brazil, Indonesia and Russia -- which now account
for half of the world's labor force but only 8 to 10 percent of
its output and trade. Given continued policy reforms and the
strengthening of an open world trade and investment regime, the
report projected, these figures could double by 2020, with
substantial repercussions for global resource allocation,
production, trade and also pricing.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani President Farooq Leghari said here
Wednesday that his country fully supported the ongoing UN efforts
for bringing about durable peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was keenly interested in the cessation of hostilities
and restoration of peace and stability in the war-torn country,
Leghari told visiting Omani Foreign Minister Yousef bin Alawi, who
 called on him at the presidential palace Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A Russian space official said Wednesday the crew of
the Mir space station has repaired the main on-board computer
which failed Monday.
</P>
<P>
The function of the gyroscopic devices, which keep the
station's solar panels in line with the sun to enable them to
generate power, was resumed. The devices failed Monday after the
computer failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
