<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Strengthens Quality Control on Products, Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Shanghai plans to upgrade the quality of major homemade industrial
products to international standards and to form several
technology-intensive transnational corporations by 2010.
</P>
<P>
In a recently-issued long-term plan on improvement of products
and service quality, the city government has decided to put more
efforts on quality control rather than merely increasing outputs
in a bid to hone the competitive edge of major industries in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Take cars and elevators, for example. The warrantied
trouble-free driving distance for Shanghai-made cars in 2000
should reach 60,000 km, yet elevators by that year are only
allowed two breakdowns in 60,000 operations.
</P>
<P>
For other products shown to have high consumer interest, the
plan said that 99 percent of major durable electrical appliances
should be operate smoothly as soon as they are removed from the
box, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
As the second step, the long-term plan stipulates that all
major products manufactured by local industries in 2010 should
meet the international criteria.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the quality of local cars should reach the
internationally-acknowledged standards in terms of gas consumption
and emission reduction.
</P>
<P>
The functions and power consumption of Shanghai-made electrical
appliances were also required to meet the needs of the overseas
consumers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smooth Sailing in Hong Kong, Says U.S. Senator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- United States Senator Craig
Thomas said today that things have gone smoothly in Hong Kong
since China resumed the exercise of its sovereignty in July.
</P>
<P>
Thomas made the remarks after a meeting between nine members of
the 15-member Senate Foreign Relations Committee and Tung Chee
Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
"I was very impressed with his observations with regard to what
has happened since the changeover," Thomas told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Things have gone smoothly."
</P>
<P>
Thomas chairs the Subcommittee of East Asian and Pacific
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the briefing, Tung said they had "a very
useful discussion, where we all understand each other's position."
</P>
<P>
Tung, who is on a four-day visit to the U.S., told reporters
that he explained to the senators about "the transition, about
what happened since the transition."
</P>
<P>
Some legislators were concerned that there might be a change of
course following China's resumption of the exercise of Hong Kong's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In a luncheon speech at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, Tung said
that the political structure in Hong Kong is functioning normally
and effectively while the lifestyle has been maintained since the
transition.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Tung and the senators also discussed the
election next year in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I have explained to them that we are moving forward in
accordance to the basic law, and we are moving forward in what we
think is very important to Hong Kong, and is in the long-term
interest of Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that there are differences between him and the
senators. "Obviously you can understand that given the different
history, different culture, we all have different beliefs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who arrived here on Monday, will leave for New York on
Thursday following meetings with U.S. congressmen on Wednesday and
a luncheon sponsored by the Asian Society. He will return on
Friday for a meeting with President Bill Clinton at the White
House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
