<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time a clear majority of voters support
Australia becoming a republic, reflecting a dramatic shift in
opinion among voters who were previously uncommitted on the issue.
A poll taken for the newspaper shows 54 percent of Australians
believe their country should be a republic.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian federal government has bowed to industry and
popular pressure, imposing a five-year freeze from 2000 on
slashing tariffs in the struggling textile, clothing and footwear
industry aimed at protecting 96,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The coroner's office in the state of Victoria may launch a
retrospective investigation into suicides linked to gambling after
a sharp rise in deaths last year. Thirteen suicides in 1996 were
linked to gambling problems, compared with just one in 1992, the
year poker machines were introduced into the state.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Optus Communications will deliver a blow to Australia's
telecommunications giant Telstra's float plans today when it files
a damages claim of up to 657 million U.S. dollars in the Federal
Court alleging misuse of market power.  
