<HEADLINE> China, UN Help Women Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and China
have signed up to a project to reduce health hazards for Chinese
women workers, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The project, involving a grant of 960,000 US dollars from the
UN Development Program (UNDP) and one million yuan (120,000 US
dollars) from the Chinese government, will last from 1997 to 2000,
the paper says.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women leaders, including mayors and managers of
township and village enterprises at municipal and county level
will be the main beneficiaries of the projects, the paper reveals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women workers have been exposed to production hazards
for a long time. Reports have poured in recently on the death or
injury of women workers across the country, especially in the
south where the economy is developing briskly, the paper says.
</P>
</TEXT>
