<HEADLINE> Small Stocks Set More New Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Smaller-company stocks on
Wall Street advanced to another record high on Tuesday, but
efforts to revive the blue-chip sector failed again.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average was up nearly 64 points about
an hour before the close, but rose just 16.73 to 7,851.91 in a
similar performance of Monday's afternoon stumble.
</P>
<P>
Smaller-company shares, meanwhile, have been soaring to new
heights. The Russell 2000 index of secondary stocks cruised to its
ninth consecutive record close.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-7 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 502.11 million shares
as against Monday's modest tally of 466.44 million.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 2.42 to 933.62, and
the NYSE composite index rose 0.91 to 486.69.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 rose 1.76 to 437.75 for its 12th consecutive
winning session, a streak that's boosted the small-company measure
by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated
by smaller companies, rose 0.76 to 671.43 for its sixth consecutive
record close.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 10.87 to 1,652.22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
