<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Second Annual Arrangement Under ESAF for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved the second annual arrangement for
Burkina Faso under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility
(ESAF), in an amount of 18 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The funding is provided in a support of the government's
economic program covering July 1, 1997 to June 30, 1998. The loan
is made available in two equal semiannual installments, the first
of which can be drawn on September 15, this year.
</P>
<P>
The economic program for 1997-98 focuses on achieving a further
increase in the budgetary revenue to GDP ratio and an acceleration
of structural reforms. The major objectives include a real GDP
growth rate above 6 percent, contain the inflation rate at 3
percent and reduce the external current account deficit to 10.5
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects. The loans carry an interest rate of 0.5 percent a year
and are repayable over 10 years, with a 5.5 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Burkina Faso joined the IMF in May 1963. Its quota is about 60
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 85 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits Two-week Low Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar suffered its
worst one-day drop against the yen in a month on Tuesday, but rose
against the mark as prospects for higher German interest rates
dimmed.
</P>
<P>
The dollar sharply reversed its recent rally against the yen
after U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers was quoted
as saying Washington is worried Japan will rely too heavily on
exports to revive its economy, which would further widen its trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 118.93 yen,
down 2 percent from 121.17 late Monday. It was the biggest drop
since a 3 percent slide on August 9.
</P>
<P>
Also in New York, the dollar settled at 1.8135 marks, up from
1.8068.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.5881 U.S. dollars, up from
1.5820 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Against the mark, the dollar was bolstered by German
unemployment unexpectedly hitting its highest level for August
since World War II. The report was seen as evidence that Germany's
economy is not growing fast enough to call for an interest-rate
hike by its central bank.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4885 Swiss francs, up from 1.4840; 6.0965 French francs, up from
6.0760; 1,766.00 Italian lire, up from 1,759.00; and 1.3839
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3827. 
</P>
</TEXT>
