<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Firm Puts Superconductor in Commercial Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. superconductor
company today announced the first sale of its superconducting
magnetic energy storage device to a foreign customer.
</P>
<P>
The power quality system was produced by American Superconductor
Corp. (AMSC) and purchased by Eskom, Africa's largest electricity
supplier and one of the five largest utilities in the world, AMSC
said in a press release from Baltimore, Md.
</P>
<P>
The device was installed at the South Africa Pulp and Paper
Industry paper mill located in Stanger, South Africa, it said.
</P>
<P>
The sale came after the first commercial launch of the
superconductor product sold to a U.S. customer in June.
</P>
<P>
The products protect industrial manufacturing operations from
the momentary voltage dips common to electric power systems.
</P>
<P>
"The cost of downtime associated with momentary outages and
voltage dips lasting less than one second is more than 12 billion
U.S. dollars per year in the United States alone, and accounts for
80 and 90 percent of all plant shutdowns related to power
quality," AMSC president Greg Yurek was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
AMSC, based in Westborough, Mass. and founded in 1987, leads
superconductor research and development for commercial use in the
global electric power industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
