<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7-Up Change Flavor to Challenge Sprite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The maker of 7-Up is changing
its flavor to make it less sweet and give it a crisper taste --
that is, more like market leader Sprite, according to the reports
of local press here.
</P>
<P>
Marketed in the late 60s as "the Uncola," 7-Up rocketed in
sales. But in the past decade, 7-Up has been losing market share
to Coca-Cola Co.-owned Sprite and now holds only 40 percent of the
lemon-lime drink category.
</P>
<P>
Dr Pepper/Seven Up, the beverage maker, will announce the
flavor change next Monday in San Antonio, a source close to the
company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mike Martin, a spokesman for Dr Pepper/Seven Up in Dallas, said
the company had no comment.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported that one person who has tasted
the drink said the product "is a nice improvement and has more of
a lemon-lime taste." Others familiar with the plans said the
product received a positive response from consumers and 7-Up
bottlers during taste testing.
</P>
<P>
Reformulating soft drinks can be risky. Coca-Cola fooled with
Coke in 1985 and protests quickly forced it to bring back the old
flavor under the name Coca-Coca Classic.
</P>
<P>
7-Up has been around for nearly 70 years, starting out in 1929
in St. Louis. Its maker, the Howdy Corp., soon shortened the name
to 7UP Lithiated Lemon Soda.
</P>
<P>
Howdy changed its name to The Seven-Up Co. in 1936, and by the
late 1940s 7-Up had become the world's third best-selling soft
drink. Prior to the early 1980s, 7-Up was the unquestioned leader
in the lemon-lime beverage segment.
</P>
<P>
However, Coca-Cola has been aggressively pushing Sprite for the
last several years, and gaining much of the market shares. 7-Up's
market share declined to 2.4 percent in 1996 from 3.2 percent in
1987.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, Sprite captured a 5.8 percent share of the 54
billion U.S. dollar soft-drink market, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
