<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Moldova's Economic Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved a 45 million U.S. dollar equivalent of a Structural
Adjustment Credit and a 55 million dollar Structural Adjustment
Loan to back Moldova's economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
The financing will be used to support government reforms
necessary to create conditions for a resumption of growth and an
improvement in living standards in Moldova.
</P>
<P>
It will also provide necessary foreign exchange to purchase
imports critical for the country's economic activity. The reform
program supported by the World Bank credit and loan will address
key bottlenecks and enhance the prospects of long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries, on standard IDA terms and
will be payable in 35 years, including a 10 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Since Moldova joined the World Bank in 1992, the Bank
commitments have totaled some 257 million dollars for 9 projects in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
