<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government to Allow Electronic Tax Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Seeking to boost electronic
filing of tax returns, the U.S. Internal Revenue Service (IRS)
said today it also plans to allow Americans to pay the taxes they
owe electronically in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Acting IRS Commissioner Michael Dolan said that taxpayers could
permit the Automated Clearing House, a computerized bank payments
system, to transfer money from their checking accounts to pay
their tax bills. The IRS now allows direct deposit of tax refunds
through a similar electronic payment system.
</P>
<P>
Dolan made the announcement at a hearing of the Ways and Means
oversight subcommittee of the U.S. House of Representatives. The
hearing was held on ways to improve electronic filing of tax
returns, which a recent IRS study commission said was a key
element of reform for the tax collection agency.
</P>
<P>
Of the 118 million individual tax returns filed this year, only
19.1 million were filed either through computers or a special
touch-tone telephone filing program, the U.S. Treasury Department
said.
</P>
<P>
And despite the explosive growth of personal computers and
online services, just 366,000 taxpayers filed their taxes
electronically using their home computers and tax preparation
software.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Treasury Department said more than 60 million
taxpayers could have had their returns filed electronically this
year because they were prepared on computers by tax preparers but
filed on paper, not through computer modems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
