<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Asian Americans Incidents Rising, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Hate crimes against Asian
Americans rose 17 percent last year despite a drop in overall
violence in the United States, according to a report released
today by a national civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
The report, by the National Asian Pacific American Legal
Consortium, said there were 534 suspected and confirmed anti-Asian
incidents in 1996, up from 458 in 1995. They included two murders,
two bomb threats, an arson attack and many types of harassment.
</P>
<P>
In Orange County, California, last year, a Vietnamese American
was stabbed repeatedly while in-line skating on a high school
tennis court. Two assailants affiliated with white supremacist
group were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Racial motivation was confirmed in 90 percent of the cases and
suspected in the rest, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The consortium said the social environment was hostile toward
Asian Americans, who number 9.7 million, about 3.7 percent of the
overall population.
</P>
<P>
"Asian Pacific Americans remained the 'perpetual foreigner' and
were denied fair political access, social acceptance and equal
opportunity in American life," it said.
</P>
<P>
It cited many cases of racist slogans, hate mail and abusive
telephone calls directed at Asian Americans seeking political
office.
</P>
<P>
After a leader of the Organization of Chinese Americans
appeared on NBC's "Today Show," she received a hate message from
an unknown caller: "You know you people are lucky we let you stay
in this country. You dumb gooks should all be sent back to China."
</P>
<P>
The group attributed the increase in anti-Asian incidents to a
general anti-immigrant atmosphere spurred by last year's passage
of a restrictive immigration reform bill, welfare legislation
denying benefits to legal immigrants, and a "general anti-minority
rhetoric" that intensified during the 1996 election year.
</P>
<P>
Executives of the organization are scheduled to meet Attorney
General Janet Reno today to discuss ways to address the issue as
part of a White House conference on hate crimes in November.
</P>
<P>
The report called for tougher federal action to deter, monitor
and prosecute hate crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
