<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Considers Adding Capital Account Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Against the background of a
recovery in world economic growth and of increasing globalization,
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) says to consider adding the
capital account liberalization as a goal.
</P>
<P>
In its 284-page Annual Report 1997, which is released here
today, the IMF noted that a great progress has been made by many
industrial and developing countries as well as transition
economies within the context of an increasingly close integration
of markets for goods, services and capital. The growing economic
interdependence of countries worldwide presented both new
opportunities and new challenges, accentuating the benefits of
good policies and the costs of bad policies.
</P>
<P>
In facing the challenges posed by growing economic integration,
the report said, the IMF acted to review further its surveillance
operations, including in the areas of banking soundness, data
dissemination, and good governance, to adapt its financial
instruments and procedures, and to examine the adequacy of its
quota resources.
</P>
<P>
In another significant development, the Interim Committee of
the IMF's Board of Governors, meeting in April 1997, endorsed the
concept of an amendment to the Articles of Agreement that would
make the promotion of capital account liberalization one of the
purposes of the IMF and give the IMF appropriate jurisdiction over
capital movements.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996/97 which ended on April 30, the IMF approved 28
new Stand-By, Extended and Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility
(ESAF) arrangements, totaling SDR 5.3 billion, which is equivalent
to more than 7.1 billion U.S. dollars in new commitments, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that this represented a big decline in the demand
for IMF resources as compared with commitments of SDR 19.7 billion
(some 27 billion dollars) in 1995/96 and SDR 16.6 billion (about
23 billion dollars) in 1994/95. Total IMF credit outstanding at
the end of the year was SDR 40.5 billion which is some 55.3
billion dollars equivalent, a slight decline from the level of SDR
42.0 billion a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
