<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Assures US on Hong Kong's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa reassured here today U.S. business leaders and political
figures that Hong Kong will maintain its momentum of development
after it returned to China's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in
Washington D.C.,Tung said:"I can assure you that Hong Kong will
continue to manage its economy with the lightest and most steady
of hands, sticking firm to free markets, small government, low
taxes and fiscal prudence."
</P>
<P>
He said that he was completely confident about Hong Kong's
future because the Basic Law has given the Special Administrative
Region (SAR)"full autonomy."
</P>
<P>
"The Basic Law gives us far more than financial autonomy. Apart
from foreign affairs and defense, it gives us full responsibility
to maintain our own economic and social systems; our own legal
system; our own system of government; our religious freedoms,
press freedom and civil liberties," said the chief executive who
arrived here Monday for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Tung to visit the United States since
he took office as chief executive at the end of 156 years of
British colonial rule. He said he would try to convince the
Americans of Hong Kong's continued stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong returned to China's sovereignty on July 1. It was a
"date to which we in Hong Kong had looked forward with pride and
confidence," Tung said, in an apparent effort to ease worries by
some Americans.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to speak for Hong Kong, but how others perceive our
country, China, has quite an impact on us," said the chief
executive, commenting on American media's negative coverage of
Hong Kong and China.
</P>
<P>
speaking highly of the "one country two systems", a brainchild
of China, Tung said:"The Central Government has given us an
entirely free hand in dealing with our own affairs and developing
our economic, social and cultural relations."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that "The success of Hong Kong under
'one country two systems' will serve as a significant step toward
the greater and final objective of reunification of the entire
Chinese nation."
</P>
<P>
Apparently responding to alleged setback on democracy in Hong
Kong, Tung said:" In seven years time we will have more democracy
in Hong Kong than we did under 156 years of colonial rule."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has never had a single voice in the selection of the
Governor during 156 years of colonial rule. Under the Basic Law,
Hong Kong people will have an increasingly larger voice in the
selection of the Chief Executive," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung also highlighted the already strong economic links between
Hong Kong and America and how increased Sino-U.S. trade would also
be good for the SAR.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 U.S. citizens live in Hong Kong and 414 U.S.
companies have regional headquarters there, while 29 U.S. banks
and financial services groups manage over 100 billion U.S. dollars
in loans, debt and assets.
</P>
<P>
" A point that everyone in Hong Kong profits from is the fact
that the U.S. and China make a good economic fit," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Around 60 percent of U.S. trade with China passes through Hong
Kong, while the direct Hong Kong - U.S. trade totals 22.4 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tung is scheduled to meet some U.S. Congressmen by Wednesday.
He is going to meet with President Bill Clinton Friday before
leaving for home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
