<DOCNO> XIE19970910.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holland to Have Bigger Population in Future: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands, which has a
population of over 15.5 million people but only an area of less
than 42,000 square kilometers, will become even more crowded in
the next few decades, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the population will have grown to about
17.2 million by 2030, but numbers will probably start to go down
after that year, says a report published by the Dutch Ministry of
Education, Culture and Science.
</P>
<P>
Before long, international migration will be the most important
reason for the rising population, which will also mean a
strengthening of the multi-cultural character of Dutch society,
according to the report entitled Population Issues in the
Netherlands 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands has one of the youngest populations in Europe,
which means potential for further growth through births. The
report says that the growth will persist for longer than in the
rest of the European Union even though the pace has slackened off
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
By around 2020, the aging of the Dutch population will mean
that births and deaths will balance one another. After this, the
number of deaths will overtake the number of births, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
It also says that the continued growth of the population will
then be entirely due to international migration. At present,
migration accounts for more than 20 percent of the annual growth
of 0.5 percent in the population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
